const CLF_QUESTIONS = [{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A startup wants to launch a web application globally without purchasing servers or paying upfront costs. Which cloud benefit enables this?","options":["Paying a fixed monthly fee for reserved capacity","Signing a 3-year contract for discounted server rates","Trade capital expense for variable operational expense with pay-as-you-go pricing","Purchasing physical servers in each target region"],"answer":2,"explain":"Cloud computing transforms CapEx (buying servers upfront) into OpEx (paying for what you use). This eliminates upfront investment and lets startups scale spending with actual usage."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company's e-commerce site experiences 10x traffic during Black Friday. What cloud benefit allows them to handle this automatically?","options":["High availability through multiple data centers","Elasticity — automatically scaling resources up and down based on demand","Economies of scale from shared infrastructure","Global reach through CDN distribution"],"answer":1,"explain":"Elasticity is the ability to automatically provision and de-provision resources to match demand. AWS Auto Scaling adds capacity during Black Friday peaks and removes it after, paying only for what was used."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which cloud deployment model keeps all infrastructure on-premises with no cloud connectivity?","options":["Private cloud — dedicated infrastructure operated solely for one organization","Public cloud using shared AWS infrastructure","Hybrid cloud combining on-premises and public cloud","Community cloud shared among organizations with similar requirements"],"answer":0,"explain":"Private cloud deploys dedicated infrastructure exclusively for one organization, either on-premises or in a dedicated hosted facility. All resources are isolated from other organizations."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company uses both AWS for new workloads and keeps legacy apps on-premises. What deployment model is this?","options":["Pure public cloud using only AWS services","Private cloud with on-premises resources only","Hybrid cloud combining on-premises and AWS cloud resources","Multi-cloud using multiple public cloud providers"],"answer":2,"explain":"Hybrid cloud integrates on-premises infrastructure with public cloud services. AWS Direct Connect and VPN provide secure connectivity between the data center and AWS, enabling workload portability."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"AWS operates data centers in multiple geographic locations worldwide. What is each distinct geographic location called?","options":["AWS Region — geographic area with multiple availability zones","Availability Zone — isolated data center within a region","Edge Location — CloudFront CDN point of presence","Local Zone — AWS infrastructure extension near cities"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Regions are distinct geographic areas (us-east-1, eu-west-1, etc.) each containing multiple Availability Zones. Choosing the right region affects latency, compliance, and disaster recovery."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A startup wants to launch a web application globally without purchasing servers or paying upfront costs. Which cloud benefit enables this?","options":["Paying a fixed monthly fee for reserved capacity","Signing a 3-year contract for discounted server rates","Trade capital expense for variable operational expense with pay-as-you-go pricing","Purchasing physical servers in each target region"],"answer":2,"explain":"Cloud computing transforms CapEx (buying servers upfront) into OpEx (paying for what you use). This eliminates upfront investment and lets startups scale spending with actual usage."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS concept describes the ability to acquire resources instantly and release them when no longer needed, with no human interaction?","options":["On-demand self-service — provision resources without human intervention","Broad network access through internet connectivity","Resource pooling sharing infrastructure among multiple customers","Measured service tracking resource usage for billing"],"answer":0,"explain":"On-demand self-service is a fundamental cloud characteristic: users can provision compute, storage, and networking resources instantly through a console or API without requiring human assistance from the provider."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company benefits from AWS's massive scale which allows AWS to offer lower prices. What cloud benefit does this represent?","options":["Elasticity scaling resources with demand","Increased speed and agility launching resources in minutes","Massive economies of scale driving lower pay-as-you-go prices","Global reach deploying in multiple regions"],"answer":2,"explain":"Because AWS serves hundreds of thousands of customers, it achieves economies of scale that result in lower variable costs, which AWS passes on through lower prices than any single company could achieve on its own."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A developer can launch a new server on AWS in minutes instead of the weeks required to procure physical hardware. What cloud advantage is this?","options":["Elasticity handling variable workloads efficiently","Economies of scale reducing infrastructure costs","Increased speed and agility — provision resources in minutes not months","Stop guessing capacity by scaling based on actual demand"],"answer":2,"explain":"Cloud dramatically increases speed and agility: resources that took weeks to procure (purchase order, shipping, rack, configure) now take minutes via console or API, enabling rapid innovation and experimentation."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company's e-commerce site experiences 10x traffic during Black Friday. What cloud benefit allows them to handle this automatically?","options":["High availability through multiple data centers","Elasticity — automatically scaling resources up and down based on demand","Economies of scale from shared infrastructure","Global reach through CDN distribution"],"answer":1,"explain":"Elasticity is the ability to automatically provision and de-provision resources to match demand. AWS Auto Scaling adds capacity during Black Friday peaks and removes it after, paying only for what was used."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Under the AWS shared responsibility model, which of the following is AWS responsible for?","options":["Encrypting customer data stored in S3","Patching the hypervisor and physical host infrastructure","Managing IAM users and their permissions","Configuring security groups on EC2 instances"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS manages and patches the physical infrastructure, hypervisor, and managed service software. Customers manage their OS patches, application security, IAM, and network configuration."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS Support plan provides access to a Technical Account Manager (TAM) and is designed for enterprise customers with mission-critical workloads?","options":["Basic Support — free tier with documentation access","Developer Support — business hours email support","Business Support — 24/7 phone and chat support","Enterprise Support — TAM plus proactive guidance"],"answer":3,"explain":"Enterprise Support includes a dedicated Technical Account Manager (TAM) who provides proactive guidance, architectural reviews, and helps customers plan, deploy, and optimize their AWS environments."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company wants to migrate its data center to AWS to eliminate the cost of managing physical hardware. What cloud benefit does this represent?","options":["Go global in minutes by deploying in multiple regions","Increase speed and agility through rapid resource provisioning","Stop spending money running and maintaining data centers","Trade variable expense for capital expense"],"answer":2,"explain":"Eliminating data center operations (power, cooling, physical security, hardware refresh cycles) is a core cloud benefit. Companies redirect that capital and staff effort toward innovation rather than infrastructure maintenance."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which cloud deployment model keeps all infrastructure on-premises with no cloud connectivity?","options":["Private cloud — dedicated infrastructure operated solely for one organization","Public cloud using shared AWS infrastructure","Hybrid cloud combining on-premises and public cloud","Community cloud shared among organizations with similar requirements"],"answer":0,"explain":"Private cloud deploys dedicated infrastructure exclusively for one organization, either on-premises or in a dedicated hosted facility. All resources are isolated from other organizations."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS service provides a unified view of all AWS accounts and enables consolidated billing for an organization?","options":["AWS Organizations for multi-account management and consolidated billing","AWS IAM for identity management across accounts","AWS Control Tower for account governance automation","AWS Config for compliance tracking across accounts"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Organizations groups multiple AWS accounts under a master payer account, enabling consolidated billing (single invoice, volume discounts), service control policies, and centralized account governance."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company wants to stop guessing how much infrastructure capacity they need. Which cloud benefit addresses this?","options":["Benefit from massive economies of scale reducing fixed costs","Trade capital expense for variable expense with pay-as-you-go","Stop guessing capacity — scale up or down as actual needs change","Go global in minutes using multiple AWS regions"],"answer":2,"explain":"With AWS, you provision based on actual demand instead of peak estimates. If you over-provision, you pay for idle capacity. Under-provision and you can't handle load. AWS Auto Scaling eliminates this guessing game."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A retail company operates stores across 50 countries and wants their customers to access content with low latency. Which AWS Global Infrastructure component enables this?","options":["AWS Regions for processing data in customer locations","AWS Availability Zones for redundancy within each country","AWS Edge Locations for caching content globally near end users","AWS Local Zones for enterprise applications"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Edge Locations (part of CloudFront) cache content globally much closer to end users than regions, providing low-latency content delivery. This reduces download times and improves user experience for geographically distributed audiences."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which of the following is an example of a managed AWS service where AWS handles patching, scaling, and availability?","options":["EC2 instance where you install and manage your own database","Amazon RDS — AWS manages database engine, backups, patching, and failover","EC2 with a self-managed Kubernetes cluster","An EC2-hosted application behind an Elastic Load Balancer"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon RDS is a managed database service — AWS handles database patching, automated backups, Multi-AZ failover, and scaling. You manage database configuration and data, not the underlying infrastructure."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A startup is designing a healthcare platform and wants to understand cloud service models. Which service model provides complete control over the operating system?","options":["SaaS — using a fully managed healthcare application","PaaS — using managed deployment platforms","IaaS — using EC2 to manage OS, middleware, and application","DaaS — using desktop-as-a-service"],"answer":2,"explain":"IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service) provides virtualized compute resources where the customer manages the OS, middleware, and application. EC2 is the classic example."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company needs to choose between deploying in a single large EC2 instance vs many smaller ones. What AWS design principle do multiple smaller instances support?","options":["Cost optimization through instance consolidation","Performance efficiency using the most powerful instance types","Design for failure — assume any component can fail and architect to survive it","Operational excellence through simplified management"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Well-Architected Pillar: Reliability. Design for failure means assuming any single component will fail. Multiple smaller instances across AZs means no single failure takes down the application."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company evaluates whether to migrate to AWS. On-premises requires $500,000 upfront hardware + $100,000/year operations. AWS costs $25,000/month. When does AWS become cost-effective?","options":["Immediately, because monthly cost is less than annual","After 7 years when cumulative costs are equivalent","After approximately 1.5 years when total costs favor AWS","After 5 years when both reach equivalent cost"],"answer":2,"explain":"TCO comparison: Year 1 on-premises = $600,000. Year 1 AWS = $300,000. Year 2 on-premises = $100,000. Year 2 AWS = $300,000. AWS becomes cheaper in Year 2 (~18 months)."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which pillar of the AWS Well-Architected Framework focuses on running and monitoring systems to deliver business value and continuously improve processes?","options":["Security — protecting information and systems","Reliability — ensuring workload performs correctly consistently","Operational Excellence — running and improving operations effectively","Performance Efficiency — using resources efficiently"],"answer":2,"explain":"Operational Excellence covers automation of operations, responding to events, and continuously improving processes and procedures. It includes performing operations as code and making small, reversible changes."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company wants to evaluate their AWS architecture against best practices. Which free AWS tool provides this assessment?","options":["AWS Well-Architected Tool for structured architectural review","AWS Trusted Advisor checking against best practices","AWS Config evaluating resource configuration compliance","AWS Inspector scanning for security vulnerabilities"],"answer":0,"explain":"The AWS Well-Architected Tool provides a consistent process to review architectures against the six pillars, identify high-risk issues, and generate improvement plans through a series of questions."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A manufacturing company states 'We no longer maintain our own data centers.' Which cloud benefit is this describing?","options":["Economies of scale from AWS managing resources for thousands of customers","Agility through infrastructure automation and rapid deployment","High availability through global infrastructure and redundancy","Elasticity to scale resources automatically based on demand"],"answer":0,"explain":"Economies of scale is where AWS's massive infrastructure serving millions of customers drives down per-unit costs through shared resources and efficiency individual companies cannot achieve."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What distinguishes a 'serverless' architecture from a traditional server-based one?","options":["Serverless uses no computing resources at all","Serverless requires more configuration than traditional server management","Serverless is only suitable for small applications under 100 users","Serverless means you don't provision or manage servers — the cloud provider handles scaling and availability automatically"],"answer":3,"explain":"Serverless (Lambda, DynamoDB, S3) means you write code or use services without provisioning or managing servers. AWS handles scaling, patching, and availability automatically. You pay only per invocation/usage."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is a key characteristic of cloud computing related to how multiple customers use the same physical infrastructure?","options":["On-demand self-service with instant provisioning","Rapid elasticity scaling resources up and down on demand","Measured service billing based on actual consumption","Resource pooling serving multiple customers from shared physical resources with multi-tenancy"],"answer":3,"explain":"Resource pooling is a core cloud characteristic where the provider serves multiple customers from a shared pool of physical resources, with customers getting virtual resources from a common infrastructure, achieving economies of scale."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS program helps customers migrate workloads to AWS by providing credits, training, and technical resources?","options":["AWS Free Tier for experimenting with AWS services","AWS Marketplace for purchasing third-party software","AWS Migration Acceleration Program (MAP) for enterprise migrations","AWS Partner Network for technology partner solutions"],"answer":2,"explain":"The AWS Migration Acceleration Program (MAP) provides financial, operational, and technical support including migration credits, training, and AWS Solutions Architect engagement for large-scale enterprise migrations."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is the difference between 'vertical scaling' and 'horizontal scaling' on AWS?","options":["Vertical scaling adds more instances; horizontal adds more capacity to one instance","Vertical scaling increases the size/power of one instance; horizontal scaling adds more instances","They are identical approaches with different AWS service names","Vertical scaling is for databases; horizontal scaling is for web servers only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Vertical scaling (scale up) increases instance size (t3.medium → m5.large). Horizontal scaling (scale out) adds more instances behind a load balancer. Horizontal is preferred for cloud-native, fault-tolerant architectures."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company wants to test a new idea by spinning up resources for 2 hours, testing, then shutting down with minimal cost. What cloud benefit supports this?","options":["Ability to experiment quickly and cheaply — provision, test, then de-provision paying only for 2 hours","Economies of scale reducing long-term infrastructure costs","High availability ensuring continuous uptime during testing","Global reach for deploying tests in multiple regions"],"answer":0,"explain":"Cloud enables cheap experimentation — try new ideas with minimal cost and risk. Failed experiments can be shut down immediately. This accelerates innovation cycles compared to waiting weeks and spending thousands on physical hardware."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"An e-commerce business uses AWS but maintains legacy systems on-premises for compliance. What cloud deployment model is this?","options":["Hybrid cloud combining on-premises infrastructure with AWS public cloud","Private cloud with AWS-managed dedicated resources","Multi-cloud using AWS and other cloud providers","Public cloud with additional public cloud services"],"answer":0,"explain":"Hybrid cloud combines on-premises infrastructure with public cloud resources (like AWS), allowing organizations to maintain legacy systems while leveraging cloud benefits."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS service provides a global network of content delivery that caches content at edge locations near end users?","options":["Amazon Route 53 for global DNS routing","Amazon CloudFront CDN for caching content at edge locations","AWS Global Accelerator for network performance optimization","Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration for fast uploads"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon CloudFront is a CDN with 400+ edge locations globally. It caches static and dynamic content near users, reducing latency and offloading origin servers. It integrates with S3, EC2, and custom origins."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A startup reviews the AWS Well-Architected Framework. What are the main architectural pillars?","options":["Cost, Security, Speed, and Compliance","Operational Excellence, Security, Reliability, Performance Efficiency, Cost Optimization, and Sustainability","Availability, Scalability, Durability, and Redundancy","AWS services, features, pricing, and support"],"answer":1,"explain":"The AWS Well-Architected Framework consists of 6 pillars: Operational Excellence, Security, Reliability, Performance Efficiency, Cost Optimization, and Sustainability. These guide cloud architecture decisions."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"AWS has data centers across the globe. What is the benefit of this global infrastructure for customers?","options":["All data is automatically replicated across all regions","All AWS services are available in every region simultaneously","Global infrastructure eliminates the need for disaster recovery planning","Customers can deploy applications globally in minutes to reduce latency for users worldwide"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS's global infrastructure of 30+ regions enables companies to deploy applications close to users worldwide in minutes, reducing latency. Previously, global expansion required years of physical infrastructure setup."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to control which AWS services their developers can use across all accounts in their organization. Which service enforces this?","options":["IAM policies attached to individual user accounts","AWS Organizations Service Control Policies (SCPs) restricting services at the organizational level","AWS Config rules monitoring service usage compliance","AWS CloudTrail logging all service API calls"],"answer":1,"explain":"Service Control Policies (SCPs) in AWS Organizations set maximum permission guardrails across all accounts in an OU or organization. Even account admins can't exceed SCP boundaries, enabling centralized governance."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service allows you to create and manage encryption keys used to protect your data, with full audit trails?","options":["AWS Key Management Service (KMS) for creating and managing cryptographic keys","AWS Certificate Manager for SSL/TLS certificates","AWS Secrets Manager for storing application credentials","AWS CloudHSM for dedicated hardware security modules"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS KMS creates and manages Customer Master Keys (CMKs) for encrypting data across AWS services. It provides centralized key management, automatic rotation, and full CloudTrail audit logs of key usage."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company needs to store database passwords and API keys securely with automatic rotation. Which AWS service is purpose-built for this?","options":["AWS KMS storing encryption keys","AWS Secrets Manager for securely storing and rotating credentials","AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store for configuration data","Amazon S3 with server-side encryption for secret files"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Secrets Manager stores, manages, and automatically rotates secrets like database passwords, API keys, and OAuth tokens. It integrates with RDS, Redshift, and DocumentDB for native credential rotation."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is multi-factor authentication (MFA) and why is it critical for AWS root accounts?","options":["An additional authentication factor beyond password, critical for root accounts to prevent account takeover","A backup authentication method used only when passwords expire","A compliance requirement only for regulated industries","An optional feature only needed for production accounts"],"answer":0,"explain":"MFA requires a second factor (TOTP app, hardware key) beyond the password. AWS root accounts have unrestricted access to all resources — if compromised, attackers can delete everything. MFA is mandatory best practice for root."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service monitors for malicious activity and unauthorized behavior across your AWS account using ML and threat intelligence?","options":["Amazon GuardDuty detecting threats using ML and threat intelligence","AWS Config tracking configuration changes","AWS Security Hub aggregating security findings","Amazon Inspector scanning for vulnerabilities"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon GuardDuty analyzes CloudTrail logs, VPC Flow Logs, and DNS logs using ML and threat intelligence to detect threats like credential compromise, unusual API calls, and crypto mining without requiring agents."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company needs to assess their EC2 instances for known vulnerabilities and unintended network exposure. Which service automates this?","options":["Amazon GuardDuty for threat detection","Amazon Inspector for automated vulnerability assessment of EC2 and containers","AWS Security Hub for compliance dashboard","AWS Config for configuration compliance checking"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Inspector automatically scans EC2 instances and container images for software vulnerabilities (CVEs) and unintended network exposure, generating prioritized findings with remediation recommendations."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"For an EC2 instance, what does the shared responsibility model define regarding management?","options":["AWS manages only the physical servers; customer manages everything above","AWS manages infrastructure; customer manages OS, applications, and data","Customer manages the infrastructure; AWS provides billing and support","AWS manages everything including applications and data"],"answer":1,"explain":"The shared responsibility model divides duties: AWS handles hardware, virtualization, networking. Customer handles OS, application software, data, and security configurations."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A developer accidentally commits AWS access keys to a public GitHub repository. What should be done immediately?","options":["Change the IAM user's password to prevent unauthorized access","Contact GitHub to remove the committed keys from history","Enable MFA on the account and wait 24 hours for the keys to expire","Deactivate and delete the exposed access keys immediately, then create new ones"],"answer":3,"explain":"Exposed access keys must be immediately deactivated/deleted in IAM — they can be used within minutes of exposure. Check CloudTrail for unauthorized usage, then create new keys and update applications."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides a centralized security dashboard aggregating findings from GuardDuty, Inspector, Macie, and other security services?","options":["Amazon GuardDuty for threat detection aggregation","Amazon CloudWatch for operational metrics and alarms","AWS Security Hub for centralized security posture management","AWS Config for compliance and configuration tracking"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Security Hub aggregates security findings from multiple AWS services and partner tools into a single dashboard, normalizes findings using ASFF format, and provides automated compliance checks (CIS, PCI, HIPAA)."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A healthcare provider needs 99.99% uptime for patient records. What cloud architecture characteristic enables this?","options":["Elasticity to scale capacity during demand peaks","High availability through redundancy across multiple Availability Zones","Economies of scale reducing operational costs","Global reach to serve patients worldwide"],"answer":1,"explain":"High availability uses redundancy across multiple Availability Zones and automated failover to ensure systems continue operating even during component failures. This meets stringent uptime requirements."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service enables compliance with regulations by recording all API calls made within your AWS account?","options":["AWS CloudTrail logging all API calls for audit and compliance","Amazon CloudWatch for performance monitoring and alerting","AWS Config tracking resource configuration changes over time","Amazon GuardDuty detecting suspicious API usage patterns"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS CloudTrail logs every API call made in your AWS account including who made it, what was done, and when. This audit trail is essential for security investigations, compliance audits, and detecting unauthorized actions."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company must comply with PCI DSS for credit card data. Which AWS program provides compliance reports and certifications?","options":["AWS Trusted Advisor checking security best practices","AWS Security Hub running PCI DSS compliance checks","AWS Artifact providing on-demand access to AWS compliance reports and certifications","AWS Config rules for PCI DSS configuration compliance"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Artifact provides on-demand access to AWS security and compliance reports (SOC 2, PCI DSS, ISO 27001, HIPAA BAA) through a self-service portal, enabling customers to demonstrate AWS's compliance posture to auditors."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A developer designs microservices where services communicate asynchronously. Why is this 'loosely coupled' architecture beneficial?","options":["It reduces the total amount of code required","Services can fail independently without cascading failures and scale independently","It automatically encrypts all communication","It eliminates the need for databases"],"answer":1,"explain":"Loose coupling means services don't depend directly on each other. One service can fail or be updated without affecting others. This improves resilience and flexibility — key cloud-native benefits."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service protects web applications from common exploits like SQL injection and cross-site scripting (XSS)?","options":["AWS Shield protecting against DDoS attacks","AWS WAF (Web Application Firewall) filtering malicious web traffic","Amazon GuardDuty detecting web-based threats","Amazon Inspector scanning web applications for vulnerabilities"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS WAF filters HTTP/HTTPS traffic using configurable rules, blocking common web attacks (OWASP Top 10 including SQL injection, XSS), bad bots, and rate-based rules. It integrates with CloudFront, ALB, and API Gateway."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to protect against large-scale DDoS attacks at the network and transport layers automatically. Which AWS service provides this for free?","options":["AWS WAF filtering application-layer attacks","AWS Shield Standard protecting all AWS customers automatically at no charge","Amazon GuardDuty detecting volumetric attack patterns","AWS Firewall Manager managing WAF rules centrally"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Shield Standard is automatically included for all AWS customers at no cost. It provides always-on protection against common network layer (Layer 3/4) DDoS attacks on EC2, ELB, CloudFront, and Route 53."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A DevOps team's application continues functioning when a database node fails by using replicas. What is this capability?","options":["High availability — the system continues operating despite component failures","Disaster recovery — restoring the entire system from backups","Failover — automatically switching to backup infrastructure","Redundancy — having duplicate components"],"answer":0,"explain":"Fault tolerance (closely related to high availability) is the system's ability to continue operating and serving requests even when individual components fail. Redundant database replicas exemplify this."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"An organization reviews AWS's principle of least privilege for security. What does this mean?","options":["Give all users full administrative access for simplicity","Grant users only the minimum permissions necessary for their jobs","Limit access only to AWS employees","Allow everyone to access resources but log all activity"],"answer":1,"explain":"Least privilege means granting only the specific permissions required for a user or service to perform their job — nothing more. This minimizes the blast radius if credentials are compromised."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to detect if sensitive data like credit card numbers is stored in their S3 buckets without their knowledge. Which service helps?","options":["Amazon GuardDuty monitoring S3 access patterns","Amazon Inspector scanning S3 objects for vulnerabilities","AWS Config checking S3 bucket configuration compliance","Amazon Macie using ML to discover and protect sensitive data in S3"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon Macie uses ML to automatically discover, classify, and protect sensitive data (PII, financial data, credentials) in S3, providing visibility into what sensitive data you have and where it's stored."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS compliance program specifically addresses healthcare data protection requirements in the United States?","options":["HIPAA — AWS signs Business Associate Agreements for covered healthcare workloads","PCI DSS for payment card industry compliance","SOC 2 Type II for service organization controls","ISO 27001 for information security management"],"answer":0,"explain":"HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act) governs US healthcare data. AWS signs Business Associate Agreements (BAAs) and provides HIPAA-eligible services with appropriate safeguards for PHI."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A CFO asks about vendor lock-in with AWS. Which factor best addresses this concern?","options":["AWS owns all customer data and can hold it hostage","Customers can export data using standard formats and migrate to other providers","AWS legally guarantees zero switching costs","Vendor lock-in is impossible; all clouds are identical"],"answer":1,"explain":"While some AWS services are proprietary, customers can export data in standard formats. Migration has switching costs, but isn't technically impossible. It's a trade-off between cloud benefits and flexibility."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to centrally manage firewall rules across multiple AWS accounts and VPCs. Which service provides this?","options":["AWS WAF managing web application firewall rules per account","Amazon Inspector centrally managing vulnerability scanning","AWS Organizations SCPs restricting security service usage","AWS Firewall Manager centrally managing security policies across accounts"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Firewall Manager centrally configures and manages WAF rules, AWS Shield Advanced, Security Groups, and Network Firewall policies across multiple accounts in AWS Organizations from a single place."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A European company with GDPR data requirements wants to deploy their application. Where should they use AWS?","options":["Use AWS US regions and hope GDPR doesn't apply","Deploy in AWS Europe (London, Frankfurt, Stockholm) regions to keep data in Europe","Use AWS global content delivery to bypass regional requirements","GDPR compliance is not relevant to AWS infrastructure"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Regions are geographically separate locations. To comply with GDPR and data residency requirements, applications and data must be deployed in specific regions (eu-west-1, eu-central-1, etc.)."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides single sign-on (SSO) access to multiple AWS accounts and business applications?","options":["AWS IAM for identity management across AWS accounts","Amazon Cognito for customer-facing application authentication","AWS IAM Identity Center (SSO) for unified access to AWS accounts and apps","AWS Directory Service for Active Directory integration"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS IAM Identity Center (formerly AWS SSO) provides centralized SSO to multiple AWS accounts and SAML 2.0 applications (Salesforce, Office 365) using a unified portal, integrating with Active Directory."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company stores all infrastructure configuration in code (Terraform, CloudFormation). How does this support security?","options":["Infrastructure as Code reduces security risks by eliminating manual console access","IaC eliminates the need for security testing of infrastructure","IaC automatically encrypts all resources defined in the templates","IaC enables consistent security configurations, version control, and peer review of infrastructure changes"],"answer":3,"explain":"Infrastructure as Code (IaC) improves security by enabling peer review of changes, enforcing consistent security configurations, detecting drift, and providing audit history of all infrastructure modifications."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A media company designing a video platform requires compute, storage, and database. Which service model provides infrastructure control with managed services?","options":["Pure SaaS — using only fully managed third-party applications","IaaS — using EC2 and S3 with self-managed databases","PaaS — using RDS, S3, and serverless for less operations","DaaS — using desktop-as-a-service"],"answer":2,"explain":"PaaS balances control and operations: managed RDS, S3, and Lambda provide cloud benefits without heavy operations overhead. Ideal for teams wanting cloud benefits without server management."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides dedicated, single-tenant hardware security modules (HSMs) for generating and using your own encryption keys?","options":["AWS KMS using shared multi-tenant hardware","AWS Certificate Manager for SSL/TLS certificate management","AWS Secrets Manager for application credential storage","AWS CloudHSM with dedicated single-tenant HSM hardware"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS CloudHSM provides dedicated HSM hardware exclusively for your use. Unlike shared KMS, CloudHSM meets compliance requirements (FIPS 140-2 Level 3) where keys must never leave a dedicated hardware device."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company receives an AWS abuse notification that their EC2 instance is sending spam emails. What should they do first?","options":["Immediately investigate the instance for compromise, isolate it, and respond to AWS abuse team","Ignore it since AWS may have made an error in detection","Terminate the instance immediately and file an insurance claim","Change the security group to block all outbound traffic and continue operations"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS abuse notifications should be taken seriously immediately. Isolate the instance (modify security group, snapshot), investigate for compromise (check processes, logs), remediate, and respond to abuse@amazonaws.com within 24 hours."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the AWS Shared Responsibility Model's customer responsibility for Amazon RDS?","options":["Patching the database engine software and OS","Ensuring RDS Multi-AZ failover works correctly","Maintaining physical hardware and hypervisor for RDS instances","Managing database schema, data encryption, and access control (IAM, security groups)"],"answer":3,"explain":"For RDS, AWS manages OS patching, database engine patching, hardware, and Multi-AZ failover. Customers are responsible for database-level security (user accounts, permissions), data encryption settings, and security group configuration."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which of the following is a customer's responsibility under the shared responsibility model for Amazon EC2?","options":["Maintaining the physical host servers and network hardware","Providing power, cooling, and physical security for the data center","Ensuring the hypervisor is secure and properly isolated between instances","Patching the operating system, managing applications, and configuring security groups"],"answer":3,"explain":"For EC2 (IaaS), customers own the guest OS — they must patch it, secure the applications, manage IAM credentials, configure security groups, and encrypt their data. AWS owns everything below the hypervisor."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to encrypt data in transit between their application and an RDS database. What should they enable?","options":["S3 server-side encryption for data stored in the database","SSL/TLS encryption for connections between the application and RDS endpoint","AWS KMS encryption keys for the RDS volume","VPC peering to prevent traffic from traveling over the public internet"],"answer":1,"explain":"Encryption in transit uses SSL/TLS to encrypt data as it travels between the application and RDS. RDS provides TLS certificates; applications must enable SSL in their connection string."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"An architect explains: 'We pay for compute resources by the second when running.' Which cloud pricing benefit is this?","options":["Reserved pricing forcing long-term commitments","Spot instances for always-on workloads","Pay-as-you-go model charging only for consumed resources","Consolidated billing discounts"],"answer":2,"explain":"Pay-as-you-go pricing charges only for resources actively used. This is the fundamental cloud cost model enabling scalability without upfront investment."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides a managed, scalable solution for DDoS protection with 24/7 access to the DDoS Response Team?","options":["AWS Shield Standard included automatically for all customers","AWS Shield Advanced for enhanced DDoS protection with DRT access","AWS WAF filtering application-layer DDoS attacks","Amazon CloudFront absorbing volumetric DDoS traffic at edge"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Shield Advanced provides enhanced DDoS detection, near real-time visibility, cost protection for DDoS-related scaling charges, and 24/7 access to the DDoS Response Team (DRT) for incident support."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to ensure only their own encryption keys protect their S3 data, with AWS never having access to the plaintext keys. What option achieves this?","options":["SSE-S3 using AWS-managed keys automatically","S3 Object Lock preventing key access to AWS","SSE-KMS using Customer Managed Keys in AWS KMS","SSE-C — customer-provided encryption keys where the customer controls and stores keys outside AWS"],"answer":3,"explain":"SSE-C (Server-Side Encryption with Customer-Provided Keys) allows customers to provide their own encryption keys with each request. AWS performs the encryption but never stores the key, providing maximum key control."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What AWS feature allows you to define and enforce which regions AWS resources can be created in?","options":["IAM policies with region conditions restricting service access","AWS Organizations SCPs with region restriction conditions","AWS Config rules monitoring resource regions","Both IAM policies and SCPs can enforce region restrictions"],"answer":3,"explain":"Region restrictions can be enforced both through IAM policies (Condition: aws:RequestedRegion) and SCP conditions. SCPs provide organization-wide enforcement that individual account admins cannot override."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A nonprofit mentions: 'We focus on our mission instead of managing servers.' Which benefit are they describing?","options":["Elasticity to handle traffic spikes","Agility — offloading infrastructure management to AWS","High availability through redundancy","Global reach across regions"],"answer":1,"explain":"Agility is offloading infrastructure complexity (servers, networking, updates, patches) to AWS so teams focus on applications and business logic."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service integrates with Microsoft Active Directory to provide directory services in the AWS cloud?","options":["AWS Directory Service providing managed Active Directory in AWS","AWS IAM Identity Center replacing Active Directory","Amazon Cognito for enterprise directory integration","AWS Organizations for multi-account directory management"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Directory Service offers managed Microsoft Active Directory (AWS Managed Microsoft AD), Simple AD, and AD Connector for connecting to on-premises AD. It enables EC2 instances to join a domain and use AD authentication."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company needs to meet GDPR requirements for data stored in AWS. What is their primary responsibility?","options":["The customer is responsible for data classification, access controls, processing purposes, and data subject rights management","AWS is fully responsible for GDPR compliance for all customer data","GDPR only applies to European AWS regions, not global deployments","AWS Artifact provides GDPR compliance that covers customer data automatically"],"answer":0,"explain":"GDPR compliance is a shared responsibility. AWS provides compliant infrastructure (certified data centers, data processing agreements). Customers are responsible for their data — what they collect, how they process it, and honoring data subject rights."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Comparing cloud deployment models, which is shared by multiple organizations but not the public?","options":["Public cloud — shared by all","Private cloud — single organization only","Hybrid cloud — on-premises plus public cloud","Community cloud — shared by organizations with similar requirements"],"answer":3,"explain":"Community cloud is shared among organizations with similar requirements (same industry, compliance needs) but not open to the general public. It's between private and public models."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company needs a scalable object storage solution for storing millions of images with 99.999999999% durability. Which service should they use?","options":["Amazon EBS block storage attached to EC2 instances","Amazon EFS elastic file system for shared storage","Amazon S3 object storage with eleven 9s of durability","Amazon Glacier for long-term archival storage"],"answer":2,"explain":"Amazon S3 provides 99.999999999% (11 nines) of durability by redundantly storing data across multiple AZs. It's designed for unlimited scalability and is the standard for object storage in AWS."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to run a web server without managing the operating system, patching, or scaling. Which AWS service best fits?","options":["Amazon EC2 with auto-managed OS patching","Amazon ECS running containers on managed EC2 clusters","AWS Elastic Beanstalk deploying applications without managing underlying infrastructure","Amazon Lightsail for simple VPS management"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Elastic Beanstalk is a PaaS that automatically handles deployment, capacity provisioning, load balancing, auto-scaling, and health monitoring. You upload code and Beanstalk manages the infrastructure."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which EC2 pricing model offers up to 90% discount for fault-tolerant workloads that can tolerate interruption?","options":["On-Demand Instances with per-second billing","Reserved Instances with 1 or 3-year commitment","Spot Instances using spare EC2 capacity at discounted prices","Dedicated Hosts for compliance and licensing requirements"],"answer":2,"explain":"EC2 Spot Instances use spare AWS capacity at up to 90% discount. AWS can reclaim Spot Instances with a 2-minute warning. Ideal for batch processing, data analysis, and fault-tolerant workloads that can checkpoint and resume."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company runs a database that requires consistent compute performance 24/7 for the next 3 years. Which pricing model provides the lowest cost?","options":["On-Demand Instances for maximum flexibility","Spot Instances for maximum discount","Reserved Instances with 3-year All Upfront payment","Savings Plans with compute flexibility"],"answer":2,"explain":"Reserved Instances with a 3-year all-upfront commitment provide the maximum discount (up to 72% off On-Demand) for steady-state workloads with predictable usage. All-upfront maximizes savings vs monthly or partial upfront."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides managed relational databases with automated backups, Multi-AZ failover, and no OS management?","options":["Amazon DynamoDB for NoSQL database management","Amazon Aurora for cloud-native relational databases only","Amazon Redshift for data warehousing","Amazon RDS for managed relational databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, etc.)"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon RDS manages relational database engines (MySQL, PostgreSQL, MariaDB, Oracle, SQL Server, Aurora) with automated backups, point-in-time recovery, Multi-AZ high availability, and automated patching."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A startup needs a NoSQL database that can handle millions of requests per second with single-digit millisecond latency. Which service is best?","options":["Amazon DynamoDB fully managed NoSQL with consistent single-digit ms performance","Amazon RDS MySQL with read replicas for scaling","Amazon ElastiCache Redis for in-memory caching","Amazon Neptune for graph database workloads"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon DynamoDB is a fully managed serverless NoSQL database delivering consistent single-digit millisecond performance at any scale, from zero to millions of requests per second with no capacity planning required."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company reviews AWS Availability Zones. What is the primary purpose of AZs in AWS regions?","options":["AZs are geographically distant to serve customers worldwide","AZs are separate data centers within a region enabling high availability and disaster recovery","AZs replace the need for backups","Each region has only one AZ"],"answer":1,"explain":"Availability Zones are separate, isolated data centers within each AWS region. Deploying across multiple AZs provides high availability: if one AZ fails, others continue operating."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company needs to distribute HTTP/HTTPS traffic across multiple EC2 instances with health checks and SSL termination. Which service provides this?","options":["Amazon Route 53 for DNS-based load balancing","Classic Load Balancer for legacy EC2-Classic workloads","Network Load Balancer (NLB) for ultra-low latency TCP/UDP","Application Load Balancer (ALB) for Layer 7 HTTP/HTTPS routing"],"answer":3,"explain":"ALB operates at Layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS), providing path-based and host-based routing, SSL termination, sticky sessions, and WebSocket support. It integrates with EC2, ECS, Lambda, and supports content-based routing."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company discusses cloud benefits and mentions 'infrastructure scales automatically during peak usage.' Which benefit is this?","options":["Economies of scale from bulk purchasing","Elasticity — automatically scaling resources based on demand","Global reach through multiple regions","Cost optimization through reserved capacity"],"answer":1,"explain":"Elasticity is the ability to automatically scale capacity up during traffic peaks and down during normal periods, ensuring you pay only for what you use."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which S3 storage class is designed for infrequently accessed data that still needs millisecond retrieval, at lower cost than S3 Standard?","options":["S3 Standard for frequently accessed data","S3 Standard-IA (Infrequent Access) for less frequent access with instant retrieval","S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval for archival with 1-12 hour retrieval","S3 Intelligent-Tiering automatically moving data between tiers"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 Standard-IA charges lower storage prices than S3 Standard but adds a per-GB retrieval fee. It's ideal for backups and disaster recovery data accessed monthly, with the same durability and instant retrieval as Standard."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to run containerized applications without managing EC2 instances or clusters. Which service provides serverless containers?","options":["Amazon ECS on EC2 launch type managing your own cluster","AWS Fargate running containers without managing underlying servers","Amazon EKS managing Kubernetes control plane only","AWS Batch for containerized batch processing jobs"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Fargate is a serverless compute engine for containers that removes the need to provision or manage EC2 instances. You define CPU/memory requirements and Fargate handles the infrastructure, scaling, and availability."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides a petabyte-scale data warehouse for running complex analytical queries?","options":["Amazon Redshift for petabyte-scale data warehousing and analytics","Amazon RDS for transactional relational database queries","Amazon DynamoDB for NoSQL analytical workloads","Amazon Aurora for fast cloud-native database queries"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon Redshift is a fully managed data warehouse that can query petabytes of structured and semi-structured data using standard SQL. It uses columnar storage and MPP (massively parallel processing) for fast analytical queries."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Reviewing cloud service models, which provides the most control to the customer?","options":["SaaS — no control, fully managed applications","PaaS — some control over applications and data","IaaS — maximum control; customer manages OS, middleware, and applications","Managed services — AWS manages everything"],"answer":2,"explain":"IaaS provides maximum customer control: EC2 lets you manage the OS, runtime, middleware, and applications. PaaS and SaaS provide progressively less control but less operations work."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to run their application code without any server management and pay only when their code executes. This describes which model?","options":["IaaS — Infrastructure as a Service with managed VMs","CaaS — Containers as a Service on managed Kubernetes","PaaS — Platform as a Service with managed runtime","Serverless computing using Lambda for event-driven execution"],"answer":3,"explain":"Serverless computing (Lambda) runs code only when triggered by events, scales automatically from zero to massive scale, and charges per invocation + duration. No servers, no patches, no capacity planning required."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides a fully managed message queue for decoupling application components?","options":["Amazon SNS for publish/subscribe notifications","Amazon SQS for reliable message queuing between services","Amazon EventBridge for event-driven architecture routing","Amazon Kinesis for real-time streaming data processing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon SQS provides managed message queues for decoupling producers from consumers. Messages are stored durably until processed. SQS enables microservices to communicate without direct dependencies."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to send notifications to millions of subscribers across email, SMS, and mobile push simultaneously. Which service enables this?","options":["Amazon SQS for reliable message delivery to queues","Amazon SES for transactional email delivery","Amazon SNS for pub/sub notifications to multiple subscribers across multiple protocols","Amazon Pinpoint for targeted customer communication campaigns"],"answer":2,"explain":"Amazon SNS is a managed pub/sub messaging service that fans out messages to multiple subscribers simultaneously via email, SMS, HTTP, SQS queues, and Lambda functions, supporting millions of subscribers."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company evaluates cloud resilience. Which architectural approach provides the highest reliability?","options":["Single data center for simplicity","Redundancy across multiple AZs with automated failover","Manual failover between regions","Backup-only approach"],"answer":1,"explain":"Deploying redundant resources across multiple Availability Zones with automated failover ensures high reliability: if one AZ fails, traffic automatically switches to healthy AZs."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides managed Kubernetes for running containerized applications?","options":["Amazon EKS (Elastic Kubernetes Service) for managed Kubernetes clusters","AWS Fargate for serverless container execution","Amazon ECS for AWS-native container orchestration","AWS App Runner for fully managed containerized web apps"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon EKS manages the Kubernetes control plane (API server, etcd) across multiple AZs, handling upgrades and patching. You manage worker nodes (EC2 or Fargate) and deploy standard Kubernetes workloads."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company needs to migrate a large amount of data (100TB) from on-premises to S3 but has limited internet bandwidth. Which service helps?","options":["AWS Snowball Edge physical device for offline data migration","AWS Direct Connect providing dedicated 10Gbps connection","Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration for faster uploads","AWS DataSync for network-based transfer optimization"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Snowball Edge is a physical device shipped to your location. You copy data to it and ship it back to AWS, which loads it into S3. For 100TB with limited bandwidth, this is faster and cheaper than network transfer."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides dedicated, high-bandwidth private network connectivity between on-premises and AWS?","options":["AWS VPN using encrypted tunnels over the internet","AWS Transit Gateway connecting VPCs and on-premises networks","Amazon Route 53 for DNS-based routing to AWS","AWS Direct Connect providing dedicated private network connections"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Direct Connect establishes dedicated 1Gbps-100Gbps private network connections from on-premises to AWS, bypassing the public internet for consistent performance, lower latency, and reduced data transfer costs."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company discusses AWS regions for their application deployment. Why would they deploy across multiple regions?","options":["Single region reduces costs","Multiple regions provide disaster recovery, low latency for global users, and regulatory compliance","All regions are identical so region choice doesn't matter","Regulations prohibit multi-region deployment"],"answer":1,"explain":"Multiple regions provide disaster recovery (if one region fails, others continue), low latency for global users (serve from nearest region), and compliance with data residency requirements."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A financial services company must comply with PCI DSS. Which AWS service provides compliance reports?","options":["AWS GuardDuty for threat detection","AWS Shield for DDoS protection","AWS Artifact for accessing compliance reports and certifications","AWS KMS for encryption"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Artifact provides on-demand access to AWS compliance reports (SOC reports, PCI DSS attestations, ISO certifications). Organizations use these to demonstrate compliance with regulatory requirements."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company runs a critical application on EC2 and wants to ensure it continues running even if an entire AWS Availability Zone fails. What should they implement?","options":["Use a larger EC2 instance type with more redundant hardware","Use Reserved Instances for guaranteed instance availability","Enable EC2 instance recovery for automatic restart after failure","Deploy EC2 instances across multiple Availability Zones behind a load balancer"],"answer":3,"explain":"Deploying across multiple AZs with an Elastic Load Balancer ensures the application continues running if one AZ fails. The load balancer routes traffic only to healthy instances in operational AZs."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service is a managed, serverless data integration service for discovering, preparing, and combining data for analytics?","options":["AWS Glue for serverless ETL and data catalog","Amazon Redshift for data warehousing workloads","Amazon EMR for big data processing with Spark and Hadoop","Amazon Kinesis for real-time streaming data ingestion"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Glue is a serverless ETL service with a Data Catalog that discovers schemas, crawls data sources, and transforms data for analytics. No servers to manage — pay only for compute used during job runs."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A DevOps engineer configures MFA for IAM users. Why is MFA critical for AWS security?","options":["It encrypts all network traffic","It eliminates the need for passwords","It requires a second verification beyond the password, preventing account compromise if passwords leak","It automatically backs up user accounts"],"answer":2,"explain":"MFA adds a second authentication factor (app, SMS, hardware key) beyond the password. Even if a password is compromised, attackers can't access the account without the second factor."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company needs to protect their web application from SQL injection and XSS attacks. Which service should they use?","options":["AWS Shield — protecting against DDoS attacks","AWS WAF (Web Application Firewall) — filtering malicious requests","AWS KMS — managing encryption keys","AWS GuardDuty — detecting intrusions"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS WAF protects web applications by filtering HTTP/HTTPS traffic based on rules. It blocks common attacks like SQL injection and XSS before they reach your application."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides a managed Apache Kafka-compatible message streaming service?","options":["Amazon SQS for reliable message queue processing","Amazon MSK (Managed Streaming for Apache Kafka) for Kafka workloads","Amazon Kinesis Data Streams for real-time streaming","Amazon EventBridge for event-driven architecture"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon MSK (Managed Streaming for Apache Kafka) provisions and manages Kafka clusters, handling broker provisioning, patching, and availability. It's compatible with existing Kafka applications and tools."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to build a RESTful API for their mobile app with authentication, throttling, and caching. Which AWS service manages this?","options":["AWS AppSync for GraphQL API management","Amazon API Gateway for RESTful and WebSocket API management","AWS Lambda URL for direct function invocation via HTTP","Elastic Load Balancer for HTTP request routing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon API Gateway creates, publishes, maintains, and secures RESTful and WebSocket APIs. It provides authentication (Cognito, Lambda authorizers), throttling, caching, request/response transformation, and SDK generation."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A healthcare organization must encrypt patient data at rest. What encryption method protects stored data?","options":["Encryption in transit — protecting data while moving over networks","Encryption at rest — protecting stored data with cryptographic keys","SSL/TLS — protecting web browser connections","Network encryption — protecting communication between data centers"],"answer":1,"explain":"Encryption at rest protects stored data (in S3, RDS, EBS) by encrypting it using AWS KMS keys. Even if someone physically accesses storage, data is unreadable without the encryption key."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS compute service is best for running scheduled batch jobs that process large datasets overnight?","options":["AWS Lambda for event-driven serverless execution","Amazon EC2 with scheduled Auto Scaling policies","AWS Batch for fully managed batch computing workloads","Amazon ECS for containerized application workloads"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Batch dynamically provisions optimal compute resources (EC2, Spot, Fargate) for batch jobs based on volume and requirements. It handles job scheduling, dependency management, and scales to hundreds of thousands of jobs."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to provide a shared file system accessible by multiple EC2 instances simultaneously across Availability Zones. Which service provides this?","options":["Amazon EBS volumes attached to single EC2 instances","Amazon FSx for Windows File Server for SMB protocol access","Amazon S3 for object storage accessible from EC2 via API","Amazon EFS (Elastic File System) for shared NFS file storage across multiple AZs"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon EFS is a managed NFS file system that automatically grows and shrinks, accessible simultaneously from multiple EC2 instances across multiple AZs. It's perfect for shared content repositories and CMS workloads."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A startup evaluates cloud maturity. What is the benefit of using managed AWS services over building infrastructure from scratch?","options":["Managed services cost more","Managed services handle operations (patches, backups, scaling), letting teams focus on applications","Managed services are less reliable","No operational benefits"],"answer":1,"explain":"Managed services (RDS, DynamoDB, Cognito) handle operations, backups, scaling, and maintenance. Teams focus on application logic, not infrastructure operations."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides machine learning-powered search capabilities for websites and applications?","options":["Amazon Comprehend for NLP text analysis","Amazon Kendra for intelligent ML-powered enterprise search","Amazon Elasticsearch Service for text search workloads","Amazon CloudSearch for managed search service"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Kendra uses ML to provide intelligent enterprise search, understanding natural language queries to find accurate answers from documents, FAQs, and knowledge bases rather than just keyword matching."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company needs to analyze their existing workloads to identify which EC2 instances to right-size before migrating to AWS. Which service provides this?","options":["AWS Pricing Calculator estimating costs before migration","AWS Migration Hub for tracking migration progress","AWS Compute Optimizer recommending optimal EC2 instance types","AWS Application Discovery Service collecting on-premises server data"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Compute Optimizer uses ML to analyze historical utilization metrics and recommends optimal EC2 instance types, Auto Scaling groups, EBS volumes, and Lambda memory to reduce costs and improve performance."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A network administrator creates a Security Group allowing HTTP and HTTPS traffic. What does this provide?","options":["It encrypts all traffic automatically","It acts as a stateful firewall controlling traffic at the instance level","It replaces the need for encryption","It eliminates the need for network infrastructure"],"answer":1,"explain":"Security Groups are stateful firewalls controlling traffic to EC2 instances. Rules specify allowed inbound traffic; outbound responses automatically flow back."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company transitioning to cloud asks: 'What replaces our on-premises data center?' Which AWS service is the foundation?","options":["S3 for all infrastructure","Amazon EC2 — virtual machines providing the compute foundation for cloud infrastructure","CloudFront for all services","Lambda for all compute"],"answer":1,"explain":"EC2 provides virtual machines (instances) that replicate the compute foundation of traditional data centers, but with auto-scaling and cloud benefits."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which service provides automated deployment pipelines for continuous integration and delivery (CI/CD) on AWS?","options":["AWS CloudFormation for infrastructure deployment automation","AWS Elastic Beanstalk for application deployment management","AWS Systems Manager for operational automation","AWS CodePipeline for orchestrating CI/CD workflows"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS CodePipeline orchestrates CI/CD pipelines connecting source (CodeCommit, GitHub), build (CodeBuild), and deploy (CodeDeploy, Elastic Beanstalk, ECS) stages for automated software release processes."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company implements the principle of least privilege in IAM. Why is this security best practice critical?","options":["It simplifies administration","It minimizes damage if credentials are compromised by limiting what the compromised account can do","It eliminates the need for firewalls","It has no security benefit"],"answer":1,"explain":"Least privilege minimizes the blast radius of a compromise. If an attacker gains a user's credentials, they can only access resources the user needs, not the entire infrastructure."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A developer needs user authentication for a mobile app without building a login system. Which AWS service provides this?","options":["AWS KMS for encryption key management","AWS Cognito for user authentication and identity management","AWS Shield for DDoS protection","AWS Artifact for compliance reports"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Cognito provides user directories, authentication, sign-up, MFA, and social login. Developers integrate Cognito APIs without building authentication systems from scratch."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to quickly set up a virtual desktop for remote employees without managing physical desktops or VDI infrastructure. Which AWS service helps?","options":["Amazon AppStream 2.0 for streaming individual applications","AWS Client VPN for secure remote network access","Amazon WorkSpaces for managed virtual desktop infrastructure","Amazon EC2 with Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP)"],"answer":2,"explain":"Amazon WorkSpaces provides managed cloud desktops (Windows or Linux) accessible from anywhere. AWS manages the infrastructure, patching, and backup. Employees connect via the WorkSpaces client from any device."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service enables running SQL queries directly on data stored in S3 without loading it into a database?","options":["Amazon Athena for serverless SQL queries directly on S3 data","Amazon RDS with S3 integration for external tables","Amazon Redshift Spectrum for S3 data querying","AWS Glue ETL for transforming S3 data before querying"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon Athena is a serverless interactive query service that runs standard SQL directly on data in S3 (CSV, JSON, Parquet, ORC) with no infrastructure to manage. Pay only per query based on data scanned."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A compliance officer wants visibility into AWS resource changes. Which service should they enable?","options":["AWS GuardDuty — detecting malicious activity","AWS Config — tracking resource configuration changes","AWS KMS — managing encryption","AWS Shield — blocking DDoS attacks"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Config continuously records AWS resource configuration changes, enabling compliance audits. This is essential for meeting regulatory requirements like SOC 2 and HIPAA."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"An organization needs to detect anomalous account activity and potential intrusions. Which service is designed for this?","options":["AWS WAF for application-layer protection","AWS Shield for DDoS protection","AWS GuardDuty for threat detection using machine learning","AWS KMS for encryption management"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS GuardDuty is a threat detection service using machine learning to analyze CloudTrail, DNS, and network logs, identifying potentially malicious activity and intrusions."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides a globally distributed in-memory cache to reduce latency for DynamoDB tables?","options":["Amazon ElastiCache Redis in front of DynamoDB","AWS Global Accelerator routing DynamoDB requests globally","Amazon CloudFront caching DynamoDB query results","Amazon DAX (DynamoDB Accelerator) providing microsecond read performance"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon DAX is a fully managed, in-memory cache specifically for DynamoDB, providing microsecond response times for read-heavy workloads. It's API-compatible with DynamoDB, requiring minimal code changes."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which AWS pricing model has no upfront costs and charges by the hour or second with no long-term commitments?","options":["On-Demand pricing with pay-as-you-go billing","Reserved Instances with upfront payment commitment","Spot Instances with variable pricing based on capacity","Dedicated Hosts with fixed monthly reservation fees"],"answer":0,"explain":"On-Demand pricing charges for compute, storage, and data transfer without upfront fees or minimum commitments. You pay only for what you use, making it ideal for unpredictable workloads and short-term experiments."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company has multiple AWS accounts. How can they consolidate billing and receive volume discounts across all accounts?","options":["Use AWS Organizations with consolidated billing to combine usage across all accounts","Contact AWS Sales to negotiate multi-account pricing","Create a single AWS account and share access across teams","Enable AWS Cost Explorer across all accounts for unified billing"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Organizations consolidated billing aggregates usage across all linked accounts into a single bill. Combined usage may qualify for volume tier pricing discounts on services like S3 and data transfer."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company needs to control encryption keys used for S3, RDS, and EBS. Which service should they use?","options":["AWS Secrets Manager for managing database passwords","AWS KMS (Key Management Service) for creating and controlling encryption keys","AWS CloudHSM for on-premises encryption","IAM policies for managing keys"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS KMS manages encryption keys used by AWS services. It provides key creation, rotation, access control, and CloudTrail logging of all key usage."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which AWS service allows you to set custom cost and usage budgets with alerts when spending exceeds thresholds?","options":["AWS Budgets for proactive cost and usage alerts","AWS Cost Explorer visualizing historical spending","AWS Cost and Usage Report for detailed billing data","AWS Pricing Calculator for estimating future costs"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Budgets lets you define budget thresholds for cost, usage, and Reserved Instance coverage. Alert notifications (email, SNS) trigger when actual or forecasted spending exceeds defined thresholds."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A compliance auditor requests logs of all API calls to AWS. Which service provides this audit trail?","options":["AWS CloudTrail for logging API activity","AWS CloudWatch for monitoring metrics","AWS Config for resource configuration changes","AWS VPC Flow Logs for network traffic"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS CloudTrail records all API calls with details: who (user identity), when (timestamp), what (API action), and result. This is mandatory for compliance and security investigations."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company notices a large unexpected AWS bill. Which service provides a detailed breakdown of costs by service, region, and tag?","options":["AWS Budgets for budget threshold management","AWS Cost Explorer for interactive cost visualization and analysis","AWS Cost and Usage Report for granular hourly billing data","AWS Trusted Advisor for cost optimization recommendations"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Cost Explorer provides interactive charts and graphs to analyze spending by service, region, linked account, and tags. It identifies cost trends, anomalies, and forecasts future spending based on historical patterns."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which pricing model offers flexibility to change instance types within a family while still receiving discounts compared to On-Demand?","options":["Standard Reserved Instances locked to a specific instance type","Convertible Reserved Instances allowing instance type changes within commitment","Compute Savings Plans for maximum flexibility across instance families","Spot Instances with dynamic pricing based on capacity"],"answer":2,"explain":"Compute Savings Plans (not Convertible RIs) offer the most flexibility — they apply to any EC2 instance type, region, OS, and tenancy. Convertible RIs allow exchanges within the same family but require manual exchange requests."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A security team deploys resources in a VPC and uses Security Groups and NACLs. What layered security is this achieving?","options":["Redundant and unnecessary security measures","Defense in depth — multiple security layers (network isolation + instance-level + subnet-level firewalls)","Only one of these is actually needed","No security benefit from multiple layers"],"answer":1,"explain":"Combining VPC (network isolation), Security Groups (instance-level stateful firewall), and NACLs (subnet-level stateless firewall) implements defense in depth."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company needs to enforce security compliance rules automatically. Which service helps enforce baselines?","options":["AWS Secrets Manager for managing passwords","AWS CloudTrail for logging API calls","AWS Config for tracking configurations and enforcing compliance rules","AWS Trusted Advisor for cost optimization only"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Config monitors resource configurations against custom rules and generates compliance reports. Non-compliant resources are flagged, enabling automated remediation."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A startup wants to reduce EC2 costs by committing to a consistent compute spend for 1 year. Which pricing option provides broad flexibility across instance types?","options":["Compute Savings Plans for flexible savings across any EC2 instance type","EC2 Reserved Instances for specific instance type discounts","EC2 Spot Instances for variable workload cost reduction","Dedicated Hosts for compliance and licensing optimization"],"answer":0,"explain":"Compute Savings Plans commit to a consistent hourly spend (e.g., $10/hr) for 1 or 3 years, applying discounts automatically to any EC2 instance type, family, region, OS, or tenancy — far more flexible than RIs."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which AWS service provides a detailed, granular billing report with hourly or daily line items for every AWS service usage?","options":["AWS Cost Explorer for interactive spending visualization","AWS Budgets for threshold-based cost monitoring","AWS Cost and Usage Report (CUR) for comprehensive billing data","AWS Pricing Calculator for future cost estimation"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Cost and Usage Report delivers the most detailed billing data available — hourly or daily line items for every service, resource ID, pricing details, and cost allocation tags, delivered to S3 for custom analysis."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company wants AWS to automatically alert them if their bill is forecasted to exceed $1,000 this month before they actually overspend. Which tool enables this?","options":["AWS Cost Explorer showing historical trends","AWS Trusted Advisor reviewing cost optimization opportunities","AWS Pricing Calculator estimating costs upfront","AWS Budgets with forecasted cost alerts"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Budgets can send alerts when forecasted costs are projected to exceed your budget threshold, giving you time to take action before the bill is finalized rather than after charges have been incurred."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is the AWS Support plan that provides production system impaired response within 4 hours?","options":["Basic Support — free tier with no production SLAs","Developer Support — business hours email support only","Business Support — 24/7 phone/chat with 4-hour production impaired response","Enterprise Support — 15-minute critical system down response"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Business Support provides 24/7 phone/chat/email support with response times of: 4 hours for production system impaired, 1 hour for production system down, and 24 business hours for general guidance."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What AWS service provides recommendations to reduce EC2 costs by identifying idle and underutilized instances?","options":["AWS Config checking resource configuration compliance","AWS Cost Explorer Reserved Instance recommendations","AWS Trusted Advisor identifying cost optimization opportunities","AWS Compute Optimizer right-sizing recommendations"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Trusted Advisor checks for idle EC2 instances, unattached EBS volumes, and underutilized RDS instances. AWS Compute Optimizer complements this with ML-based right-sizing recommendations for optimal instance types."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company purchases Reserved Instances for EC2 but their usage pattern changes and the RIs no longer align with their workload. What can they do?","options":["Contact AWS to cancel the Reserved Instances immediately","Sell unused Reserved Instances on the AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace","Convert Reserved Instances to On-Demand automatically","Transfer Reserved Instances between AWS accounts for free"],"answer":1,"explain":"The AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace allows customers to sell their unused Standard Reserved Instances to other AWS customers. This provides an exit option when workloads change and RIs no longer match usage."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which AWS service enables you to view and manage all of your AWS costs from a single, integrated view even across multiple payer accounts?","options":["AWS Cost Explorer for a single account cost analysis","AWS Cost and Usage Report for detailed billing data export","AWS Cost Management console providing unified cost visibility","AWS Organizations for multi-account consolidated billing view"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Cost Management console (including Cost Explorer, Budgets, Cost and Usage Reports) provides unified visibility across all linked accounts in AWS Organizations, enabling cross-account cost analysis and optimization."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to enable encryption for data in transit (moving between EC2 and database). Which technology provides this?","options":["Encryption at rest only","SSL/TLS — encrypts data while moving over networks","VPC isolation only","No encryption for data in transit"],"answer":1,"explain":"SSL/TLS encrypts data while in transit. Combined with encryption at rest, this protects data in all states (moving and stored)."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company wants to track how much each team is spending on AWS. What is the best practice for cost attribution?","options":["Create separate AWS accounts for each team","Ask teams to self-report their AWS resource usage monthly","Review monthly bills manually and estimate team costs","Use consistent cost allocation tags (e.g., team=engineering) on all resources and activate them in billing"],"answer":3,"explain":"Consistent cost allocation tagging is the scalable best practice. Tag every resource with team, project, and environment tags, activate them in billing preferences, and filter Cost Explorer by tag to see per-team spending."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company runs a web application on EC2 and experiences sudden traffic spike. How does Auto Scaling respond?","options":["Servers crash from overload","Auto Scaling automatically launches additional EC2 instances to handle the load","Manual intervention is required","No solution exists for traffic spikes"],"answer":1,"explain":"EC2 Auto Scaling Groups automatically launch instances when load increases (based on CloudWatch metrics) and terminate instances when load decreases."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which AWS tool can help identify which EC2 Reserved Instances are underutilized and recommend purchasing options?","options":["AWS Pricing Calculator for evaluating purchase options","AWS Budgets tracking RI coverage percentage","AWS Trusted Advisor checking RI utilization rates","AWS Cost Explorer with RI utilization and coverage reports"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Cost Explorer provides Reserved Instance utilization reports (how much of your RI capacity was actually used) and coverage reports (what percentage of your usage was covered by RIs), plus purchase recommendations."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company is choosing between AWS and building their own data center. Which total cost of ownership (TCO) factors favor AWS?","options":["AWS eliminates server hardware purchase, data center facility costs, power/cooling, and staff for infrastructure management","AWS always costs less than on-premises for every workload","On-premises is always cheaper for steady-state workloads with predictable demand","AWS pricing is transparent while on-premises has no hidden costs"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS TCO advantages include: no capital expenditure on hardware, no facility costs, no power/cooling expenses, no hardware lifecycle management, and reduced staff for infrastructure. AWS TCO Calculator quantifies these savings."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"AWS Trusted Advisor flags: 'security group allows unrestricted SSH access (0.0.0.0/0).' What risk does this represent?","options":["No risk; SSH is encrypted so it's always safe","High risk: anyone on the internet can attempt to connect via SSH","Risk only applies to production environments","Risk is eliminated if you use strong passwords"],"answer":1,"explain":"Allowing SSH from 0.0.0.0/0 exposes instances to brute force attacks and automated bot scanning. Best practice: restrict SSH to specific IPs or use AWS Systems Manager Session Manager."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which AWS Support plan includes Infrastructure Event Management for major launches and migrations at no additional cost?","options":["Business Support included in standard pricing","Enterprise On-Ramp for production workloads","Developer Support for growing companies","Enterprise Support providing proactive engagement including IEM"],"answer":3,"explain":"Enterprise Support includes Infrastructure Event Management (IEM), where AWS Solution Architects provide hands-on operational guidance for significant events like product launches, migrations, and high-traffic events."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What are the 6 R's of cloud migration strategies? Which strategy involves rehosting an application without changes?","options":["Rehost (lift-and-shift) — moving the application to cloud with no changes","Refactor — redesigning the application to be cloud-native","Replatform — making minor optimizations without changing core architecture","Retire — decommissioning applications that are no longer needed"],"answer":0,"explain":"Rehost (lift-and-shift) moves applications to the cloud as-is with no code changes. It's the fastest migration approach, ideal for quickly getting out of a data center. Other Rs: Replatform, Refactor, Repurchase, Retire, Retain."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company wants to replace their self-managed CRM with Salesforce on AWS. Which migration strategy is this?","options":["Rehost — moving existing CRM to EC2 without changes","Replatform — upgrading the database engine during migration","Repurchase — dropping the current app and switching to a different SaaS product","Refactor — rebuilding the CRM as cloud-native microservices"],"answer":2,"explain":"Repurchase (drop-and-shop) means abandoning the current application and purchasing a commercial off-the-shelf SaaS replacement like Salesforce, ServiceNow, or Workday. No migration of the old code needed."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A startup needs compute capacity with flexibility to scale. Which AWS service fits this?","options":["AWS Lambda for serverless functions","Amazon EC2 for virtual machine instances with auto scaling","Amazon RDS for databases only","Amazon S3 for storage only"],"answer":1,"explain":"EC2 provides resizable virtual machines where you can select instance types, OS, and applications. Auto Scaling automatically adds/removes instances based on demand."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A team runs data analytics requiring high CPU and memory. Which EC2 instance family is optimized for this?","options":["T-family for burstable workloads","C-family for compute-optimized workloads with high CPU","R-family for memory-optimized workloads","I-family for storage-optimized workloads"],"answer":1,"explain":"EC2 instance families are optimized: T (burstable general use), C (compute-optimized, high CPU), R (memory-optimized), I (storage-optimized). Choosing the right family optimizes price/performance."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company has a steady, long-term application. What EC2 pricing model minimizes cost?","options":["On-Demand pricing for maximum flexibility","Reserved Instances (1 or 3-year commitment) for 30-70% discounts","Spot Instances for 70-90% discount but can be interrupted","Dedicated Hosts for specific licensing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Reserved Instances offer 30-70% discounts for 1 or 3-year commitments. For steady, long-term workloads, RIs provide savings while maintaining flexibility."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which disaster recovery strategy offers the fastest recovery time but highest cost, by keeping a fully operational duplicate environment always running?","options":["Backup and Restore — cheapest but slowest, restore from backup when needed","Pilot Light — minimal critical systems always running, scale up when needed","Warm Standby — scaled-down but fully functional version always running","Multi-Site Active/Active — full production capacity in multiple regions simultaneously"],"answer":3,"explain":"Multi-Site Active/Active runs full production in multiple AWS regions simultaneously. Failover is instant (near-zero RTO/RPO) but costs 2x since you run full infrastructure in multiple regions. Most expensive DR strategy."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company wants the cheapest disaster recovery strategy and can tolerate several hours of downtime. Which approach should they use?","options":["Multi-Site Active/Active for zero downtime","Warm Standby with a scaled-down live environment","Pilot Light with only core database systems running","Backup and Restore — back up data to S3 and restore EC2 instances when needed"],"answer":3,"explain":"Backup and Restore is the cheapest DR strategy: back up data to S3 or AMI snapshots. During disaster, provision new resources from scratch. Recovery takes hours but costs near zero when not in use."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS service helps track the cost of AWS resources by assigning metadata labels to resources for cost allocation?","options":["AWS Budgets setting spending alerts","AWS Trusted Advisor recommending cost optimizations","AWS Cost Explorer analyzing spending patterns","Cost allocation tags identifying and tracking resource costs by project or team"],"answer":3,"explain":"Cost allocation tags are key-value pairs (e.g., Project=Analytics, Team=Engineering) attached to AWS resources. After activation in Billing, they appear in Cost Explorer and detailed billing reports for granular cost tracking."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to serve static website assets globally with low latency. Which AWS service is designed for this?","options":["EC2 instances in multiple regions","Amazon CloudFront — a CDN caching content at edge locations worldwide","Amazon RDS for database-backed content","AWS Lambda for serverless websites"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront is AWS's CDN. It caches content at 400+ edge locations globally, serving cached content from locations nearest users, reducing latency dramatically."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS Support plan is the minimum required to get 24/7 phone and chat access to Cloud Support Engineers?","options":["Basic Support — free but limited to documentation and forums","Developer Support — business hours email support only","Business Support — 24/7 phone and chat with Cloud Support Engineers","Enterprise Support — dedicated TAM plus 24/7 support"],"answer":2,"explain":"Business Support (from $100/month) is the minimum plan with 24/7 phone and chat access to AWS Cloud Support Engineers. Developer Support only provides business hours email. Enterprise adds a dedicated TAM."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What response time SLA does Business Support provide for production system down cases?","options":["24 hours — next business day response","12 hours — same day business hours response","4 hours — urgent response for impaired production systems","1 hour — for production system down cases"],"answer":3,"explain":"Business Support guarantees: <1 hour for production system DOWN, <4 hours for production IMPAIRED, <12 hours for general guidance. Enterprise Support offers <15 minutes for business-critical systems down."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS tool provides automated recommendations across cost, performance, security, fault tolerance, and service limits?","options":["AWS Config checking configuration compliance against rules","AWS Well-Architected Tool for structured architecture review","AWS Trusted Advisor providing real-time best practice recommendations","Amazon CloudWatch monitoring metrics and setting alarms"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Trusted Advisor inspects your AWS environment and provides actionable recommendations in 5 categories: Cost Optimization, Performance, Security, Fault Tolerance, and Service Limits. Business/Enterprise plans get full checks."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"An application needs to store objects like files, images, and videos. Which AWS service is optimized for this?","options":["Amazon EC2 for compute and storage","Amazon RDS for structured databases","Amazon S3 for object storage with unlimited scalability","Amazon DynamoDB for NoSQL tables"],"answer":2,"explain":"Amazon S3 is an object storage service optimized for files and unstructured data. It offers unlimited scalability, high durability, and integrates with many AWS services."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company archives data rarely accessed. Which S3 storage class optimizes for long-term archival?","options":["S3 Standard for frequently accessed data","S3 Glacier or S3 Glacier Deep Archive for archival with very low cost","S3 Intelligent-Tiering for automatic optimization","S3 One Zone-IA for single AZ infrequent access"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 Glacier/Glacier Deep Archive offer the lowest costs for long-term archives but require retrieval time (minutes to hours/days)."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which cloud deployment model uses dedicated hardware for a single organization, hosted and managed by a third-party provider?","options":["Public cloud — multi-tenant shared AWS infrastructure","On-premises private cloud — owned and operated by the organization","Hosted private cloud — dedicated hardware managed by a third party","Hybrid cloud — combining on-premises with public cloud"],"answer":2,"explain":"Hosted private cloud uses dedicated (single-tenant) infrastructure but the hardware is hosted and managed by a provider like AWS Outposts or managed hosting companies. Combines dedicated resources with managed operations."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A developer uses Amazon S3 and wants to prevent accidental deletion of critical objects. Which S3 feature provides this?","options":["S3 has no deletion protection","S3 Object Lock — protects objects from deletion/overwrite for compliance (WORM)","Only S3 Glacier provides protection","Deletion is always immediate"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 Object Lock enables Write Once Read Many (WORM) mode, preventing objects from being deleted or overwritten even by root account. Essential for compliance archives."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which pricing model allows customers to commit to a consistent compute usage amount in exchange for up to 72% discount vs On-Demand?","options":["On-Demand — pay for compute by the hour with no commitment","Spot Instances — bid for unused EC2 capacity at up to 90% discount","Reserved Instances or Savings Plans — commit to usage for 1 or 3 years for discount","Dedicated Hosts — pay for a physical server dedicated to your use"],"answer":2,"explain":"Reserved Instances (1 or 3 year commitment) and Savings Plans offer up to 72% discount vs On-Demand in exchange for usage commitment. Best for steady-state workloads with predictable resource requirements."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company is migrating and wants AWS to help identify which applications to move first. Which service provides migration assessment and planning?","options":["AWS Schema Conversion Tool for database migration","AWS Migration Hub for tracking migrations across services","AWS Application Discovery Service gathering on-premises data for migration planning","AWS Database Migration Service for moving databases"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Application Discovery Service collects data about on-premises servers (performance, dependencies, configurations) to help plan migrations. It feeds into Migration Hub for tracking migration progress across DMS and SMS."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company needs a managed relational database without managing software or hardware. Which service fits?","options":["EC2 instances with self-managed MySQL","Amazon RDS — managed relational database (MySQL, PostgreSQL, Oracle, SQL Server, Aurora)","Amazon DynamoDB for NoSQL only","Amazon S3 for structured data"],"answer":1,"explain":"RDS is a managed service: AWS handles patches, backups, failover, replication, and maintenance. You define instance type and storage; AWS handles the rest."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A startup evaluates Aurora versus traditional RDS. What is Aurora's primary advantage?","options":["Cheaper than RDS","Up to 5x faster than RDS with automatic scaling and high availability","Suitable only for NoSQL workloads","Requires manual database administration"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aurora is AWS's proprietary relational database optimized for performance (5x MySQL speed) and cost, with automatic scaling and high availability."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which Well-Architected pillar focuses on the ability of a workload to perform its intended function correctly and consistently, and recover from failures?","options":["Operational Excellence — running and improving operations","Security — protecting information and systems","Reliability — recovering from failures and meeting demand","Performance Efficiency — using resources efficiently"],"answer":2,"explain":"The Reliability pillar covers: automatic recovery from failure, testing recovery procedures, horizontal scaling, stopping guessing capacity, and managing change through automation. Key services: Route 53, RDS Multi-AZ, Auto Scaling."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company runs batch processing jobs triggered on-demand. Which service optimizes cost?","options":["Running EC2 instances 24/7","AWS Lambda — serverless compute triggered on-demand, paying per invocation","Amazon ECS for container orchestration","AWS Batch only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda is ideal for event-driven, short-duration jobs: no servers to manage, pay per invocation (first 1 million free/month), scales automatically."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS service helps customers move petabyte-scale data to AWS when internet transfer would take too long?","options":["AWS DataSync for online data transfer via internet or Direct Connect","Amazon Kinesis for streaming real-time data to AWS","AWS Transfer Family for SFTP-based data transfer","AWS Snowball Edge — physical device that ships to your data center for offline data transfer"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Snow family (Snowball, Snowmobile) provides physical devices for offline data transfer. Snowball Edge handles 80TB per device — faster and more cost-effective than internet transfer for large datasets."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What does the 'Sustainability' pillar (6th pillar) of the AWS Well-Architected Framework focus on?","options":["Long-term business sustainability and profitability in the cloud","Ensuring workloads run sustainably without interruption","Sustainable pricing through long-term Reserved Instance commitments","Minimizing environmental impact by reducing energy consumption and carbon footprint"],"answer":3,"explain":"The Sustainability pillar (added 2021) focuses on minimizing environmental impact of cloud workloads: right-sizing resources, using graviton processors, optimizing code efficiency, and choosing regions powered by renewable energy."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A team discusses 'serverless architecture.' What does 'serverless' mean for AWS Lambda?","options":["No servers are involved","AWS manages servers: developers write functions; AWS handles provisioning, scaling, patching","Code runs without the internet","All AWS services are serverless"],"answer":1,"explain":"Serverless doesn't mean no servers; it means AWS manages servers. Developers focus on function code, not infrastructure."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS program lets startups get AWS credits, training, and support to build their businesses on AWS?","options":["AWS Free Tier for new accounts experimenting with services","AWS Migration Acceleration Program for enterprise migrations","AWS Activate providing credits, training, and support specifically for startups","AWS Marketplace for purchasing startup software solutions"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Activate provides startups with AWS credits (up to $100,000+), technical training, business support, and access to startup-focused resources through accelerators, incubators, and VC partners."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company needs a Virtual Private Cloud (VPC). What are the primary VPC components?","options":["Only EC2 instances","Subnets (public/private), Internet Gateway, NAT Gateway, Route Tables, Security Groups, NACLs","Just a security group","VPCs don't provide network isolation"],"answer":1,"explain":"A VPC is a logically isolated network with subnets, gateways (Internet, NAT), routing, and firewalls (Security Groups, NACLs)."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A financial company needs its AWS resources to only be accessible over a private dedicated network connection, not the public internet. Which service provides this?","options":["AWS Direct Connect — dedicated private fiber connection from data center to AWS","VPN Gateway using encrypted tunnels over the internet","VPC Peering connecting two VPCs privately","AWS PrivateLink for private connectivity to AWS services"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Direct Connect provides a dedicated, private fiber connection from a customer's data center to AWS, bypassing the public internet. Ideal for consistent network performance, large data transfers, and compliance requirements."},{"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is the purpose of the AWS Service Health Dashboard vs AWS Personal Health Dashboard?","options":["They are identical dashboards showing the same information","Service Health Dashboard shows all AWS service status globally; Personal Health Dashboard shows issues affecting YOUR specific resources","Service Health Dashboard is for enterprise customers; Personal Health Dashboard is for individual developers","Personal Health Dashboard costs extra; Service Health Dashboard is free"],"answer":1,"explain":"Service Health Dashboard (status.aws.amazon.com) shows global AWS service status. Personal Health Dashboard (AWS Health) shows events specifically affecting your resources and provides proactive notifications for planned maintenance."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Private database instances need internet access for updates. How is this provided securely?","options":["Private subnets cannot access the internet","Using a NAT Gateway in the public subnet for outbound-only access","Opening all ports to the internet","Private databases don't need updates"],"answer":1,"explain":"NAT Gateway in the public subnet enables private instances to initiate outbound connections while blocking inbound internet traffic."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company has multiple AWS accounts and needs a centralized place to manage all security findings. Which service provides this unified security view?","options":["Amazon GuardDuty for threat detection across accounts","AWS Security Hub aggregating findings from multiple security services across accounts","AWS Config tracking compliance across all accounts","IAM Access Analyzer analyzing resource permissions"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Security Hub provides a comprehensive view of security alerts and compliance status across AWS accounts, aggregating findings from GuardDuty, Inspector, Macie, and partner tools into a prioritized security dashboard."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"An architect designs DNS routing for global applications. Which service routes traffic geographically?","options":["AWS Lambda for serverless routing","Amazon Route 53 — AWS's DNS with geolocation routing","Amazon CloudFront only","Security Groups for routing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Route 53 provides DNS with intelligent routing: geolocation, latency-based, weighted, failover routing. This directs users to optimal endpoints automatically."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service enables single sign-on for employees to access multiple AWS accounts and business applications with one set of credentials?","options":["AWS IAM Identity Center (SSO) for centralized single sign-on across accounts and applications","AWS IAM for individual user authentication","Amazon Cognito for customer-facing application authentication","AWS Directory Service for Microsoft Active Directory integration"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS IAM Identity Center (formerly AWS SSO) provides centralized access management to multiple AWS accounts and cloud applications (Salesforce, Office 365). Employees sign in once using corporate credentials for all resources."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the difference between security groups and Network Access Control Lists (NACLs) in AWS?","options":["Security groups are for databases; NACLs are for web servers","NACLs are stricter and override security group settings","Security groups are stateful instance-level firewalls; NACLs are stateless subnet-level firewalls with explicit allow and deny rules","Security groups require more configuration; NACLs are automatically configured"],"answer":2,"explain":"Security groups: stateful (track connections), instance-level, allow rules only, evaluate all rules. NACLs: stateless (must allow return traffic), subnet-level, allow AND deny rules, process rules in number order. Both apply to VPC traffic."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is AWS Shield Advanced and when would a company need it over Shield Standard?","options":["Shield Standard for small companies; Shield Advanced only for enterprises","Shield Advanced adds DDoS cost protection, attack visibility, response team access, and advanced attack mitigation for sophisticated DDoS attacks","Shield Advanced is required for all production AWS workloads","Shield Advanced provides WAF rules; Shield Standard does not"],"answer":1,"explain":"Shield Advanced ($3,000/month) adds: 24/7 DDoS Response Team access, real-time attack visibility, cost protection (credits for DDoS-related scaling costs), advanced detection, and protection for EC2, ELB, CloudFront, Route 53, and Global Accelerator."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service helps prevent accidental public exposure of S3 buckets and other resources by analyzing resource policies?","options":["Amazon Macie scanning S3 for sensitive data exposure","Amazon GuardDuty detecting unauthorized S3 access","AWS Config checking S3 bucket public access settings","IAM Access Analyzer identifying resources accessible from outside your account"],"answer":3,"explain":"IAM Access Analyzer examines resource policies (S3, IAM roles, KMS keys, Lambda, SQS) to identify resources shared with external entities, helping find unintended public access or cross-account sharing."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Under the shared responsibility model, who is responsible for patching the operating system on an EC2 instance?","options":["AWS — they manage all software running on their infrastructure","Neither — EC2 instances automatically patch themselves","Both AWS and customer share OS patching responsibility equally","The customer — EC2 is IaaS so customers manage the OS and above"],"answer":3,"explain":"For EC2 (IaaS), customers own the OS and everything above: OS patches, application updates, runtime security. AWS manages the hypervisor and physical infrastructure. Contrast with RDS where AWS patches the database engine."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company balances traffic across multiple web servers automatically. Which service distributes traffic?","options":["Route 53 for DNS only","AWS Elastic Load Balancing (ALB, NLB, CLB) — distributes traffic with health checks","Security Groups for load balancing","EC2 Auto Scaling alone"],"answer":1,"explain":"Elastic Load Balancing automatically distributes traffic across healthy instances, removes unhealthy targets, and scales. ALB (Layer 7), NLB (Layer 4), CLB (classic)."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which compliance framework is most relevant for companies storing healthcare data (PHI) in AWS?","options":["PCI DSS for payment card data protection","HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act) for protected health information","SOC 2 for service organization security controls","ISO 27001 for information security management systems"],"answer":1,"explain":"HIPAA governs protected health information (PHI). AWS signs a Business Associate Agreement (BAA) with healthcare customers and offers HIPAA-eligible services. Customers are responsible for HIPAA-compliant configurations."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is 'encryption in transit' and which protocol implements it for web traffic?","options":["Encrypting data as it travels across networks using TLS/SSL protocols","Encrypting data on disk using AES-256 encryption","Encrypting data before it leaves your application server","Compressing data for faster network transmission"],"answer":0,"explain":"Encryption in transit (TLS/SSL) protects data moving between clients and servers, or between AWS services. AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) provides free SSL/TLS certificates for CloudFront, ALB, and API Gateway."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company needs to ensure no one in their organization can create resources in regions outside of us-east-1 and eu-west-1. What is the best approach?","options":["Create IAM policies denying all other regions for each user","Set up CloudTrail alarms for API calls in unauthorized regions","Configure AWS Config rules alerting on resources in other regions","Use AWS Organizations SCPs to deny all actions in non-approved regions"],"answer":3,"explain":"SCPs in AWS Organizations can deny all actions in non-approved regions using Condition keys like aws:RequestedRegion. This creates an organization-wide guardrail that applies to all accounts, even administrators."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What AWS service continuously monitors and records AWS resource configurations, enabling compliance auditing and change tracking?","options":["AWS CloudTrail recording all API calls made in the account","AWS Config recording resource configurations and changes over time","Amazon CloudWatch monitoring metrics and system performance","AWS Security Hub aggregating security compliance findings"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Config continuously records resource configurations and changes, evaluates against compliance rules, and maintains a configuration history. Enables questions like 'what did this security group look like 30 days ago?'"},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company stores data in RDS and wants automated failover if the primary database fails. What RDS feature enables this?","options":["Data is never replicated in RDS","RDS Multi-AZ synchronously replicates data to a standby, automatically promoting the standby on failure","Manual failover is required","Only DynamoDB supports automatic failover"],"answer":1,"explain":"RDS Multi-AZ provides high availability: synchronous replication to a standby database in another AZ with automatic failover on failure."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides managed Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) protection and is automatically applied to all AWS customers at no charge?","options":["AWS WAF — web application firewall filtering layer 7 attacks","AWS Network Firewall — managed VPC firewall service","Amazon GuardDuty — detecting volumetric attack patterns","AWS Shield Standard — automatic protection against network/transport layer DDoS at no cost"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Shield Standard is included free for all AWS customers, providing automatic protection against the most common, frequently occurring network and transport layer DDoS attacks that target AWS services."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to ensure that all EC2 instances in their AWS account always have encrypted EBS volumes. What is the most efficient way to enforce this?","options":["Manually encrypt each EBS volume when launching instances","Create an IAM policy preventing creation of unencrypted volumes","Use AWS Config rules to alert when unencrypted volumes are found","Enable default EBS encryption in the account settings to encrypt all new volumes automatically"],"answer":3,"explain":"Account-level EBS encryption default ensures all newly created EBS volumes and snapshots are automatically encrypted using KMS, without requiring any action when launching instances. This is the simplest enforcement mechanism."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company needs to alert teams when CPU usage exceeds 80%. Which AWS service provides this?","options":["AWS Config for compliance tracking","AWS CloudWatch — provides metrics, monitoring, and alarms","AWS Trusted Advisor for cost optimization","AWS Systems Manager for resource management"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudWatch collects metrics from services and resources. Alarms trigger notifications when metrics exceed thresholds."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides a fully managed network firewall for filtering traffic entering and leaving VPCs?","options":["Security groups filtering EC2 instance traffic","Network ACLs filtering subnet traffic","AWS Network Firewall providing stateful deep packet inspection for VPCs","AWS WAF filtering HTTP traffic at the application layer"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Network Firewall is a managed VPC firewall service providing stateful deep packet inspection, IPS (intrusion prevention), and URL filtering. Unlike security groups and NACLs, it supports Suricata-compatible rules for advanced threat detection."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A healthcare provider requires database high availability with automatic failover. Which service provides this?","options":["Self-managed MySQL on EC2","Amazon RDS with Multi-AZ deployment — automatic failover on failure","Amazon S3 for databases","No AWS service provides automatic failover"],"answer":1,"explain":"RDS Multi-AZ provides automatic failover: primary database is synchronously replicated to a standby in another AZ. On failure, the standby is promoted automatically."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company must demonstrate to auditors that AWS meets specific compliance standards. What self-service AWS resource provides compliance documentation?","options":["AWS Security Hub showing compliance scores and findings","AWS Config providing configuration compliance reports","AWS Artifact providing on-demand AWS compliance reports, certifications, and agreements","AWS Trusted Advisor showing security compliance best practices"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Artifact is a self-service portal providing: AWS compliance reports (SOC 1/2/3, PCI DSS, ISO), compliance agreements (HIPAA BAA, GDPR DPA), and security audit documentation for customer auditors."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A healthcare platform needs daily backups and point-in-time recovery. Which RDS feature enables this?","options":["Manual snapshots only","RDS automated backups — continuous daily backups enabling point-in-time recovery up to 35 days","S3 backup system","No automated backups available"],"answer":1,"explain":"RDS automated backups create daily snapshots retained for up to 35 days. Combined with transaction logs, this enables point-in-time recovery."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company uses CloudFront to serve content globally. What primary benefit does it provide?","options":["CloudFront is more expensive","CloudFront caches content at edge locations globally, reducing latency and bandwidth costs","CloudFront adds security","Direct S3 is faster than CloudFront"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront is a CDN caching content at 400+ edge locations. Users download from nearby edges instead of the origin, reducing latency significantly."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service enables federated access to AWS using existing corporate identities from Microsoft Active Directory?","options":["AWS IAM creating native AWS user accounts","AWS IAM Identity Center for multi-account SSO","Amazon Cognito for customer application identity","AWS Directory Service connecting AWS to Microsoft AD or running Managed AD in the cloud"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Directory Service provides options: AD Connector (proxy to on-premises AD), AWS Managed Microsoft AD (fully managed AD in AWS), and Simple AD. Enables employees to use existing Windows credentials for AWS console access."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A startup doesn't have dedicated security staff. Which AWS service provides automated security recommendations based on best practices for free?","options":["Amazon Inspector running vulnerability assessments","AWS Trusted Advisor Basic providing core security checks for free","AWS Security Hub aggregating security findings","Amazon GuardDuty providing ML-based threat detection"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Trusted Advisor Basic (free) provides core security checks: S3 bucket permissions, security group open ports, IAM usage, MFA on root, public EBS snapshots, and public RDS snapshots. A quick automated security review available to all."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What are the S3 storage classes and which is most appropriate for frequently accessed data requiring millisecond access?","options":["S3 Glacier — cheapest storage for frequently accessed data","S3 Intelligent-Tiering — automatically moves data between tiers","S3 Standard-IA — infrequent access tier for active data","S3 Standard — high durability, availability, and performance for frequently accessed data"],"answer":3,"explain":"S3 Standard: 99.999999999% durability, 99.99% availability, millisecond access, no retrieval fee. Best for frequently accessed data like web assets, active datasets. More expensive than IA tiers but no retrieval charges."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company stores compliance data that is rarely accessed but must be retrievable within 12 hours at minimal cost. Which S3 storage class is best?","options":["S3 Standard — high performance but expensive for rarely accessed data","S3 Standard-IA — lower storage cost with retrieval fee for infrequent access","S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval — low-cost archival with retrieval times from minutes to 12 hours","S3 Express One Zone — single-AZ for frequently accessed data"],"answer":2,"explain":"S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval (formerly Glacier) is for archival data: 90-day minimum storage, retrieval options from 1-5 minutes (Expedited), 3-5 hours (Standard), or 5-12 hours (Bulk). Far cheaper than S3 Standard for rarely accessed compliance data."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"An architect designs an application requiring global low-latency content delivery. CloudFront is selected for the CDN. Why?","options":["CloudFront is expensive and slow","CloudFront caches content at 400+ edge locations globally, serving users from nearby locations","CloudFront only works in the US","Direct S3 is faster than CloudFront"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront reduces latency by caching content globally at edge locations, serving users from nearby instead of making requests to the origin."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A startup needs to monitor applications for errors and performance. Which AWS service provides detailed insights?","options":["AWS CloudTrail for API logging only","AWS X-Ray — traces requests end-to-end, revealing bottlenecks and errors","Route 53 for DNS only","CloudFront for CDN only"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS X-Ray provides distributed tracing: instruments applications to track requests end-to-end, showing latency, dependencies, and errors."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company manages containers and needs orchestration. What AWS service provides this?","options":["EC2 instances only","Amazon ECS (Elastic Container Service) or EKS (Kubernetes) for orchestration","S3 for container images","Lambda for all container workloads"],"answer":1,"explain":"ECS is AWS's native container orchestration. EKS runs Kubernetes. Both handle deployment, scaling, and health checks."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A startup uses containers but wants to avoid managing infrastructure. Which service runs containers without managing servers?","options":["EC2 instances directly","AWS Fargate — serverless containers using ECS or EKS","Amazon RDS","S3 for container storage"],"answer":1,"explain":"Fargate is serverless container compute: define your container and resources; Fargate handles launching and scaling. You pay per container per second; no servers to manage."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to store container images securely. Which AWS service is a container registry?","options":["S3 for all images","Amazon ECR (Elastic Container Registry) — manages private images with built-in scanning","EC2 instances","CloudFront for images"],"answer":1,"explain":"ECR is a fully managed container registry integrating with ECS and EKS. It stores private images, performs vulnerability scanning, and integrates with IAM."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company processes high-volume data in batches. Which service is optimized for this?","options":["EC2 instances only","AWS Batch — fully managed batch computing with automatic scaling","Lambda for all batch jobs","CloudWatch for batch processing"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Batch manages batch computing: define jobs, Batch handles provisioning instances, scheduling, and scaling. Ideal for large-scale, long-running workloads."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company with variable workloads wants flexibility without long-term commitments. Which pricing model fits?","options":["Reserved Instances requiring commitments","On-Demand pricing — pay per hour/second with flexibility to scale","Spot Instances with interruption risk","Fixed pricing regardless of usage"],"answer":1,"explain":"On-Demand pricing offers maximum flexibility: pay for capacity used, no commitments, scale instantly. More expensive per unit than RIs/Spot."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company commits to a steady application for 3 years. What pricing model offers maximum savings?","options":["On-Demand for flexibility","3-year Reserved Instances for 60-72% discount","Spot Instances for interruption risk","Pay-as-you-go without analysis"],"answer":1,"explain":"3-year RIs provide 60-72% discounts (all upfront, partial, or no upfront options). For steady workloads, RIs provide the best price-to-performance."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A startup wants to reduce EC2 costs and tolerates interruptions. What pricing option is ideal?","options":["On-Demand pricing","Reserved Instances","Spot Instances — spare capacity at 70-90% discount, usable if interruptions are tolerable","No cost optimization"],"answer":2,"explain":"Spot Instances provide up to 90% discount on spare AWS capacity but can be reclaimed with 2-minute notice. Ideal for fault-tolerant, batch workloads."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides a petabyte-scale data warehouse for complex analytical queries across large datasets?","options":["Amazon RDS for relational database workloads","Amazon Aurora for high-performance relational analytics","Amazon DynamoDB for high-speed NoSQL analytical queries","Amazon Redshift — managed petabyte-scale data warehouse using columnar storage"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon Redshift is a managed data warehouse using columnar storage and massively parallel processing (MPP). Ideal for BI, analytics, and complex SQL queries across petabytes of structured data from multiple sources."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company wants reduced costs without capacity commitment. What combines savings plans with flexibility?","options":["On-Demand pricing only","AWS Savings Plans — hourly commitment discounts (up to 66%) across instance families and services","Reserved Instances","No flexible savings"],"answer":1,"explain":"Savings Plans offer flexibility: commit to $/hour (not specific instances), apply across EC2 families, regions, Lambda, Fargate. 20-66% savings."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A startup launches on AWS and wants to minimize first-year costs. What is the AWS Free Tier?","options":["All AWS services are free indefinitely","12-month free tier, always-free services, and trials","AWS is always paid","Free tier is not available"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Free Tier provides: 12-month free (EC2, RDS, S3 limits), always-free (Lambda 1M invocations, DynamoDB 25 GB), and trials. Careful: overages are charged."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company needs to forecast monthly costs before incurring them. Which AWS tool provides estimates?","options":["AWS CloudWatch for monitoring only","AWS Pricing Calculator — estimates costs based on selected services","AWS Cost Explorer for historical analysis only","No cost estimation tools available"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Pricing Calculator estimates costs: select services, configure parameters, and it calculates expected monthly costs. Helps budget before launch."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company's AWS costs are increasing unexpectedly. Which service analyzes spending and identifies drivers?","options":["AWS CloudWatch for metrics only","AWS Cost Explorer — visualizes spending, identifies drivers, and forecasts","AWS Budgets for cost limits only","CloudTrail for API logging only"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Cost Explorer breaks down costs by service, account, usage type, and region. It shows trends and forecasts future spending."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company wants alerts when AWS spending approaches a budget. Which AWS service provides this?","options":["CloudWatch alarms for infrastructure metrics only","AWS Budgets — sets cost/usage limits and triggers alerts","Cost Explorer for analysis only","No budget alerting available"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Budgets sets budget limits and sends SNS notifications when spending approaches thresholds (50%, 90%, 100%). Prevents bill shock."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company compares TCO: on-premises versus AWS. What factors should analysis include?","options":["Only hardware cost","Hardware, software, staffing (salaries), space, power, cooling, disaster recovery, and depreciation","Only compute costs","Cloud is always cheaper"],"answer":1,"explain":"TCO includes all on-premises costs: servers, software, IT staff wages, space, power, cooling, backup/DR, and maintenance. AWS typically has lower TCO."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is the difference between an Application Load Balancer (ALB) and a Network Load Balancer (NLB)?","options":["ALB operates at layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS) enabling path-based routing; NLB operates at layer 4 (TCP/UDP) for ultra-high performance","ALB is for HTTPS traffic; NLB is for HTTP traffic only","NLB is newer and should replace ALB for all use cases","ALB supports Auto Scaling; NLB requires manual scaling"],"answer":0,"explain":"ALB (Layer 7): path-based routing (/api → service A, /web → service B), host-based routing, sticky sessions, HTTP header rules. Best for microservices. NLB (Layer 4): millions of requests/second, static IP, TCP/UDP, ultra-low latency. Best for gaming, IoT."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What are EC2 placement groups and when would you use a 'Cluster' placement group?","options":["Cluster placement groups pack instances together in the same AZ for low-latency, high-throughput network performance for HPC","Groups of EC2 instances in different regions for global distribution","Groups of EC2 instances automatically distributed across AZs for high availability","Spread placement groups placing instances on different hardware for fault tolerance"],"answer":0,"explain":"Cluster placement groups put instances physically close together in one AZ, enabling 10Gbps+ network performance and low latency. Ideal for HPC, big data, and applications requiring tight node communication. Trade-off: all in one AZ (single failure domain)."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company needs 24/7 support with sub-hour response times. Which AWS support plan is appropriate?","options":["Basic plan (free, limited)","Business plan (1-hour critical response) or Enterprise plan (15-minute response)","Developer plan for paid support","Support requires additional service purchase"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Support: (1) Basic (free, limited), (2) Developer ($29/month), (3) Business ($100+/month, 1-hour response), (4) Enterprise ($15k+/month, 15-min response)."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company consolidates multiple AWS accounts. What feature enables consolidated billing?","options":["Individual bills for each account","AWS Organizations with consolidated billing and volume discounts","Cost Explorer alone","No consolidation available"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Organizations consolidates accounts under a master account, enabling consolidated billing, volume discount purchasing, and unified policies."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"AWS Trusted Advisor flags 'underutilized EC2 instances.' What does this recommendation suggest?","options":["No action needed","Instances at low utilization can be downsized or terminated to reduce costs","All instances must be fully utilized","Underutilization is unavoidable"],"answer":1,"explain":"Trusted Advisor flags instances at low utilization. Downsizing or terminating unused instances directly reduces costs."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"An organization tracks costs by project/department. How can costs be allocated and tracked?","options":["AWS doesn't support cost allocation","Cost allocation tags — tag resources; Cost Explorer filters by tags","Only account-level billing available","Manual spreadsheet tracking only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cost allocation tags (custom metadata: project, team) are applied to resources. Cost Explorer filters spending by tags, enabling departmental cost visibility and chargeback."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company transfers large amounts of data out of AWS. They see high data transfer costs. How can these be reduced?","options":["Data transfer is always expensive","AWS Direct Connect or reducing transfer frequency/volume","AWS data transfer is free","No way to optimize"],"answer":1,"explain":"Data transfer OUT of AWS incurs charges (~$0.02/GB). AWS Direct Connect provides private connectivity reducing costs. Caching via CloudFront also reduces origin transfer."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company runs containerized applications and wants managed orchestration without managing cluster nodes. What AWS service provides this?","options":["ECS with EC2 (requires managing instances)","AWS Fargate — serverless containers without managing cluster infrastructure","EC2 instances only","No managed container option"],"answer":1,"explain":"Fargate is serverless container compute: define containers and Fargate handles infrastructure. Pairs with ECS or EKS for orchestration."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides a fully managed GraphQL API that connects to DynamoDB, Lambda, and other data sources?","options":["Amazon API Gateway for RESTful API management","AWS AppSync for managed GraphQL APIs with real-time subscriptions and offline data sync","Amazon Cognito for API authentication and authorization","AWS Amplify for full-stack mobile and web application development"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS AppSync creates managed GraphQL APIs that resolve queries against multiple backends (DynamoDB, Lambda, HTTP, RDS). Supports real-time data subscriptions and offline client synchronization for mobile apps."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"An application needs to process files uploaded to S3. What is the recommended serverless approach?","options":["Polling S3 continuously with EC2","S3 event notifications triggering Lambda functions to process files","Manual file processing","Files cannot trigger automated processing"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 can emit notifications (SNS, SQS, Lambda) when objects are uploaded, triggering event-driven processing. This is serverless and cost-effective."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company runs batch jobs processing terabytes of data nightly. Which AWS service is most cost-effective?","options":["Running EC2 instances 24/7","AWS Batch — scales compute automatically for batch processing","Lambda for all batch workloads","Manual server management"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Batch automatically scales compute resources for batch jobs, launching instances when needed and terminating them after completion."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A team wants to visualize application performance and correlate it with infrastructure metrics. Which AWS service provides this?","options":["CloudTrail for API logging only","AWS CloudWatch — provides metrics, dashboards, and correlates infrastructure with application performance","Route 53 for DNS only","No visualization available"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudWatch collects metrics from AWS services and custom applications, creating dashboards to visualize performance and correlate issues."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company deploys a microservices application requiring service discovery and load balancing. What does a service mesh or AWS service provide?","options":["Service Mesh only","AWS App Mesh or Elastic Load Balancing for service discovery and traffic distribution","No AWS service for this","Manual configuration only"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS App Mesh and ELB handle service discovery (registering/discovering services) and intelligent traffic distribution across instances."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company reviews their AWS bill and sees charges for data transfer out to the internet. How can they reduce this?","options":["Data transfer is unavoidable","AWS Direct Connect reduces transfer costs; caching via CloudFront reduces origin bandwidth","Only paying upfront eliminates transfer costs","No optimization possible"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Direct Connect provides private connectivity reducing data transfer costs. CloudFront caching reduces origin bandwidth charges."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A startup wants to forecast costs for a new project before launch. What AWS tool helps with this?","options":["AWS Trusted Advisor only","AWS Pricing Calculator — estimates costs based on service configurations","Only historical data is available","No forecasting tools exist"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Pricing Calculator estimates monthly costs by selecting services and configuring parameters. Provides accurate budgeting before launch."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company uses AWS Organizations for consolidated billing. What additional benefit does Organizations provide?","options":["Only consolidates bills","Organizations enables consolidated billing, volume discounts, unified SCPs, and centralized cost visibility","No other benefits","Requires separate AWS accounts elsewhere"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Organizations consolidates accounts for billing, enables volume discounts on Reserved Instances, and allows centralized policy management via SCPs."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"An organization wants to implement chargeback for departmental cloud costs. How should they approach this?","options":["Cloud costs cannot be allocated by department","Tag resources with cost-center/project; use Cost Explorer to filter and allocate costs to departments","Manual spreadsheets only","No chargeback mechanism exists"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cost allocation tags (department, project, cost-center) enable filtering in Cost Explorer to allocate costs to departments for chargeback."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company commits $100,000/month in AWS spending. How should they purchase compute to optimize costs?","options":["On-Demand pricing for flexibility","Savings Plans committing to $/hour across instance families and services for 20-66% savings","Spot Instances for all workloads","No cost optimization"],"answer":1,"explain":"Savings Plans provide better pricing than On-Demand while maintaining flexibility across instance families and services. Ideal for predictable spending."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A startup wants to minimize costs and accept that some workloads may be interrupted. What pricing model is best?","options":["On-Demand pricing only","Spot Instances for up to 90% discount on spare capacity","Reserved Instances for all","Pay-as-you-go"],"answer":1,"explain":"Spot Instances provide the deepest discounts (70-90%) on spare AWS capacity but can be interrupted with 2-minute notice. Best for fault-tolerant workloads."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company's AWS costs increased unexpectedly. They need to identify the cause quickly. Which AWS tool provides this?","options":["AWS Trusted Advisor for cost optimization only","AWS Cost Explorer — shows spending by service, identifies anomalies and cost drivers","CloudTrail for API logging only","Manual analysis only"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Cost Explorer breaks down costs by service, region, account, and usage type. It identifies unexpected cost spikes and anomalies."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is the difference between Standard Reserved Instances and Convertible Reserved Instances?","options":["Standard RIs offer higher discounts (up to 72%) but cannot change attributes; Convertible RIs allow changing instance family/OS/tenancy with slightly lower discounts (up to 66%)","Standard RIs are monthly commitments; Convertible RIs are annual commitments","Convertible RIs are more expensive with no additional flexibility benefits","Standard RIs can be sold on the marketplace; Convertible RIs cannot"],"answer":0,"explain":"Standard RIs: highest discount (72%), can sell unused RIs on Marketplace, cannot change instance type/OS/tenancy. Convertible RIs: slightly lower discount (66%), can exchange for different RI attributes during the term. Both offer 1 or 3-year terms."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company wants to prevent budget overruns by alerting teams when costs exceed limits. Which AWS service helps?","options":["AWS CloudWatch for infrastructure metrics only","AWS Budgets — sets cost/usage limits and triggers SNS notifications when approaching thresholds","Cost Explorer for analysis only","No budget alerting available"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Budgets sets budget limits and sends notifications (SNS) when spending approaches or exceeds thresholds, preventing bill shock."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company evaluates AWS for 5-year planning. They want the lowest possible cost for a long-term commitment. What should they purchase?","options":["On-Demand pricing for flexibility","5-year Savings Plans provide deeper discounts than 1-year (if available)","Spot Instances for long-term","Reserved Instances for maximum savings"],"answer":3,"explain":"Reserved Instances offer the deepest discounts for long-term commitments. 3-year RIs are the standard; longer commitments offer better pricing."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company reviews AWS security and wants to understand encryption key management. Which service controls encryption keys?","options":["S3 for key storage","AWS KMS (Key Management Service) — manages encryption keys with IAM policies and audit logging","IAM only for key management","No key management service"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS KMS manages encryption keys used by S3, RDS, EBS, and other services. It provides key creation, rotation, access control, and CloudTrail logging."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is the difference between AWS Budgets alerts and CloudWatch billing alarms?","options":["AWS Budgets monitors actual and forecasted costs with granular filtering; CloudWatch billing alarms only trigger when actual charges exceed a threshold","They are identical services with different names in different AWS console locations","CloudWatch billing alarms are more sophisticated than AWS Budgets","AWS Budgets is for enterprises; CloudWatch billing alarms are for individual developers"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Budgets: track actual and FORECASTED costs, filter by service/tag/account, set usage budgets, 62-day alert history. CloudWatch billing alarms: simple threshold on actual spend. Budgets is more comprehensive for proactive cost management."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to prevent accidental deletion of critical AWS resources. What service helps enforce this?","options":["Security Groups prevent deletion","AWS Config enforces compliance rules; IAM policies with Deny statements prevent specific actions","No prevention mechanism exists","Deletion is always allowed"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Config can detect unauthorized deletions. IAM policies with explicit Deny statements prevent deletion of critical resources."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company runs an ecommerce site requiring real-time inventory updates across regions. Which database service provides this?","options":["RDS in single region only","Amazon DynamoDB with global tables for multi-region replication","S3 for inventory only","No real-time option"],"answer":1,"explain":"DynamoDB global tables provide multi-region replication with automatic synchronization, enabling low-latency real-time inventory across regions."},{"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is Compute Savings Plans and how does it differ from EC2 Instance Savings Plans?","options":["Compute Savings Plans apply only to EC2; EC2 Instance Savings Plans apply to all compute","Compute Savings Plans apply to EC2, Fargate, and Lambda across any region/family/OS; EC2 Instance Savings Plans offer higher discounts but are restricted to specific EC2 family and region","They have identical discounts but different service coverage","EC2 Instance Savings Plans are purchased annually; Compute Savings Plans monthly"],"answer":1,"explain":"Compute Savings Plans (up to 66% off): most flexible — applies to EC2 regardless of family/size/region, plus Fargate and Lambda. EC2 Instance Savings Plans (up to 72% off): higher discount but locked to a specific EC2 instance family and region."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to cache frequently accessed database queries for performance. What AWS service enables this?","options":["S3 for caching only","Amazon ElastiCache (Redis, Memcached) — caches data for low-latency access","RDS caching only","No caching service"],"answer":1,"explain":"ElastiCache (Redis or Memcached) provides in-memory caching, reducing database load and improving application response times."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service helps detect and protect sensitive data like credit card numbers and SSNs stored in S3?","options":["Amazon GuardDuty for detecting unauthorized S3 access attempts","Amazon Inspector scanning S3 objects for security vulnerabilities","AWS Config checking S3 bucket encryption settings","Amazon Macie using ML to discover and classify sensitive data in S3"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon Macie uses ML to automatically discover sensitive data (PII, financial data, credentials, intellectual property) in S3 buckets, classify it, and alert on policy violations. Critical for GDPR, CCPA, and PCI compliance."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"An application needs a message queue for asynchronous communication. Which AWS service provides this?","options":["S3 for messages","Amazon SQS (Simple Queue Service) — managed message queues for decoupled communication","No queue service available","Direct API calls only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon SQS provides managed message queues enabling asynchronous communication between applications and decoupling of components."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to give an EC2 instance permission to write to an S3 bucket securely without storing credentials on the instance. What is the best approach?","options":["Store IAM user access keys in a .env file on the EC2 instance","Attach an IAM role to the EC2 instance with S3 write permissions — temporary credentials are automatically provided","Create an IAM user and store credentials in Parameter Store on the instance","Use the root account credentials in the application configuration"],"answer":1,"explain":"IAM roles attached to EC2 instances provide temporary credentials via instance metadata (automatically rotated). The application calls AWS SDK/CLI and credentials are provided automatically. No keys to manage, rotate, or accidentally expose."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to stream real-time data (click events, transactions). Which AWS service handles streaming?","options":["S3 for streaming only","Amazon Kinesis — collects, processes, and analyzes streaming data at scale","CloudFront for streaming only","No streaming service"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Kinesis captures and processes streaming data (events, transactions) with low latency, enabling real-time analytics."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A development team wants to deploy their application with infrastructure as code. Which AWS service provides this?","options":["S3 for storing code only","AWS CloudFormation — provisions infrastructure using declarative templates (JSON/YAML)","EC2 manual configuration only","No infrastructure-as-code option"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS CloudFormation uses templates to declare infrastructure. This enables version control, reproducibility, and easy updates/rollbacks."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the principle of 'immutable infrastructure' and how does it improve security?","options":["Infrastructure that cannot be modified or scaled after initial deployment","Replacing servers rather than patching them in-place — ensures known good state, eliminates configuration drift and persistent access","Using hardware security modules that cannot be tampered with physically","Locking IAM permissions so they cannot be modified after creation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Immutable infrastructure: instead of patching running servers (which accumulate drift), create new AMI with updates and replace instances. Eliminates configuration drift, ensures consistent deployments, and removes persistent access from attackers who may have compromised old instances."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides automated compliance checking against standards like CIS AWS Foundations Benchmark?","options":["AWS Security Hub running automated compliance checks against CIS, PCI DSS, and other standards","AWS Trusted Advisor checking basic security best practices","AWS Config rules evaluating specific resource configurations","Amazon Inspector scanning for known CVE vulnerabilities"],"answer":0,"explain":"Security Hub runs automated, continuous compliance checks against standards: CIS AWS Foundations Benchmark, PCI DSS, AWS Foundational Security Best Practices. Provides pass/fail findings with remediation guidance across your accounts."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to monitor their EC2 instances for security events and malware. Which AWS service helps?","options":["CloudWatch metrics only","Amazon GuardDuty for threat detection; AWS Inspector for vulnerability scanning","Security Groups only","No security monitoring"],"answer":1,"explain":"GuardDuty detects intrusions and malicious activity. AWS Inspector scans for vulnerabilities in EC2 instances and container images."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is a bastion host (jump box) and what modern AWS service replaces the need for one?","options":["A highly available EC2 instance used as a primary application server","An internet-accessible instance used as a gateway to access private instances — AWS Systems Manager Session Manager eliminates the need for one","A dedicated hardware server for cryptographic key operations","A monitoring server collecting logs from all EC2 instances in a VPC"],"answer":1,"explain":"Bastion hosts are EC2 instances in public subnets used to SSH/RDP into private instances. Security risk: exposed public IP, port 22/3389 open. AWS Systems Manager Session Manager provides browser-based shell access to private instances via IAM — no bastion, no open ports."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides real-time visibility into your AWS account's adherence to security best practices and compliance standards?","options":["Amazon CloudWatch monitoring operational metrics and performance","Amazon GuardDuty detecting active threats in your account","AWS CloudTrail logging API calls for audit and investigation","AWS Security Hub providing continuous security and compliance posture management"],"answer":3,"explain":"Security Hub provides a centralized security and compliance dashboard: aggregates findings from multiple services, runs compliance checks (CIS, PCI, NIST), provides Security Score, and shows findings prioritized by severity with remediation guidance."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company stores sensitive data in S3 and wants to ensure buckets cannot be made public by accident. Which S3 feature prevents public access?","options":["S3 bucket policies only","S3 Block Public Access settings — prevents public ACLs and policies at account and bucket level","S3 encryption only","Buckets cannot be protected from public access"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 Block Public Access settings prevent public ACLs and policies from taking effect, protecting buckets from accidental public exposure. This is a critical security best practice."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A multi-account organization wants centralized security policy management and WAF rules across AWS accounts. Which AWS service provides this?","options":["CloudFront for CDN rules only","AWS Firewall Manager — manages WAF, Shield, and security groups centrally across accounts","Individual account WAF only","No centralized management"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Firewall Manager provides centralized management of AWS WAF, Shield, and security groups across multiple accounts and AWS Organizations."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is a 'confused deputy' attack and how does the aws:SourceAccount condition key prevent it?","options":["When a service acting on your behalf is tricked into acting for another account — aws:SourceAccount ensures the service only acts when called from your account","A social engineering attack targeting AWS account managers","A man-in-the-middle attack on AWS API calls between services","An attack where a confused attacker gets IAM credentials from the wrong account"],"answer":0,"explain":"Confused deputy: malicious actor tricks a service (like CloudTrail, Config) with permissions into acting on their behalf. Using aws:SourceAccount and aws:SourceArn condition keys in resource policies ensures the service only acts when called from your specific account."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company deploys AWS WAF with rate-based rules. What attack does this protect against?","options":["Physical attacks on data centers","DDoS attacks and brute force attacks — rate-based rules block IPs making excessive requests","Encryption issues","No protection from rate-based rules"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS WAF rate-based rules block IP addresses making excessive requests within a time period, protecting against DDoS and brute force attacks."},{"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company implements 'zero trust security' in AWS when deploying sensitive applications. What does this security model mean?","options":["Trust all users and services by default","Never trust any user or service by default; verify every access request with authentication and least privilege authorization","Only trust AWS services","No authentication needed"],"answer":1,"explain":"Zero trust security assumes no user or service is trustworthy by default. Every access request requires verification via strong authentication and least privilege authorization (multi-factor auth, IAM policies limiting permissions)."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What are EC2 Auto Scaling policies and what is the difference between target tracking and step scaling?","options":["Auto Scaling policies are for Reserved Instances only; On-Demand uses manual scaling","Target tracking scales horizontally; step scaling scales vertically","They are identical policies with different names for different EC2 families","Target tracking maintains a metric at a target value (e.g., 50% CPU); step scaling adds/removes capacity in steps based on alarm breach size"],"answer":3,"explain":"Target tracking: simplest — set CPU to 50%, Auto Scaling adjusts automatically. Step scaling: define scale-out steps (CPU 70%: add 2, CPU 85%: add 4). Scheduled scaling: known traffic patterns. Predictive scaling: ML-based proactive scaling."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company needs persistent block storage for EC2 instances with high performance. Which AWS service provides this?","options":["S3 for block storage","Amazon EBS (Elastic Block Store) — persistent block storage with multiple volume types (SSD, HDD, provisioned IOPS)","CloudFront for storage","No block storage available"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon EBS provides persistent block storage volumes attachable to EC2 instances. Volume types: gp3/gp2 (general purpose), io1/io2 (high performance), st1/sc1 (throughput-optimized/cold)."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A development team wants to automate building, testing, and deploying applications. What AWS service orchestrates this CI/CD pipeline?","options":["S3 for storage only","AWS CodePipeline — automates build, test, and deployment stages with CodeBuild, CodeDeploy integration","CloudFormation for infrastructure only","No CI/CD automation available"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS CodePipeline orchestrates continuous integration and deployment: CodeCommit (source) → CodeBuild (build/test) → CodeDeploy (deploy). Enables fast, automated releases."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company analyzes customer feedback text to understand sentiment. Which AWS service performs natural language analysis?","options":["S3 for text storage only","Amazon Comprehend — uses ML to analyze text for sentiment, entities, and topics","EC2 for custom analysis","No text analysis available"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Comprehend analyzes unstructured text using machine learning: detects sentiment (positive/negative), identifies entities (people, places), and extracts topics."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to build a chatbot for customer service using conversational AI. Which AWS service provides this capability?","options":["CloudFront for chatbot delivery only","Amazon Lex — ML service for building conversational chatbots with natural language understanding","RDS for chatbot databases only","No chatbot service available"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Lex powers conversational interfaces using automatic speech recognition (ASR) and natural language understanding (NLU). Used in the Alexa service."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A global company operates in multiple languages and wants to automatically translate customer content. Which AWS service provides this?","options":["CloudFront for content distribution only","Amazon Translate — translates text between languages using neural machine translation","RDS for language storage only","No translation service available"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Translate translates text between 70+ languages using neural machine translation. Useful for global customer interactions and content localization."},{"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A team debugs a microservices application with performance issues across services. Which AWS service visualizes request flows and latency?","options":["CloudWatch metrics only","AWS X-Ray — traces requests through distributed systems, visualizing latency and service dependencies","CloudTrail for API logging only","No tracing service available"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS X-Ray provides distributed tracing: instruments applications to track requests end-to-end, revealing latency in each service and identifying bottlenecks."}];